# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: biocentrism-ethics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] The **Constitution of Ecuador** is the supreme law of Ecuador.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] The current constitution has been in place since 2008.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] Following his election as President of Ecuador, Rafael Correa called for a referendum on establishing a Constituent Assembly to write a new constitution for the country, which was held on April 15, 2007, and passed with 81.7% approval.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] The elections for the Ecuadorian Constituent Assembly were held on September 30, 2007.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] With 74 seats, Rafael Correa's political party, PAIS Alliance, won the majority of the 130 available seats.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] The assembly first convened on November 29, 2007, in Montecristi, and was given six months to write a new constitution, with a possible two-month extension.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] On July 24, 2008, the assembly approved a draft constitution consisting of 494 articles.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] When Ecuador began the process of writing a new constitution, they received help from the Community Environmental Legal Defense Fund to draft environmental laws giving nature and ecosystems rights.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] The Constitution was approved by the electorate in the constitutional referendum in September 2008 by 63.93% to 28.10%.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] The Constitution is the first in the world to recognize legally enforceable rights of nature, or ecosystem rights.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] Article 71-74 prohibits the extraction of non-renewable resources in protected areas.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] Moreover, the production of monocultures will be avoided for reforestation and rehabilitation of the soil.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] The state will also protect the intellectual property of collective work based on national biodiversity and begin to recognize the rights of nature.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] The Constitution prohibits Ecuador from yielding jurisdiction over private trade or contract disputes to external organizations.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] As a result, Ecuador was forced to withdraw from the International Centre for Settlement of Investment Disputes (ICSID).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] The constitution is one of the first in the world to recognise the right to food.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] Adopt fiscal politics, tributaries and tariffs to protect the agro-food sector and national fishery to avoid dependency on food imports.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] Strengthen diversification and the introduction of ecological and organic technologies in the production of agriculture.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] Promote redistributive politics to permit access of farmers to soil, water and other productive resources.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] Establish preferential financial mechanisms for small and medium producers, facilitating the acquisition of the means of production.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] Promote the preservation and rehabilitation of agro biodiversity linked to ancestral knowledge; likewise its use, conservation and free seed exchange.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] Ensure that animals destined for human consumption are healthy and raised in sound environments.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] Assure the development of scientific investigation and innovative technologies are appropriate to guarantee food sovereignty.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] Regulate under bio-security standards the use and development of biotechnology, including experimentation and commercial use.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] Strengthen the development of organizations and networks of producers and consumers and the commercialization and distribution of food to promote equity within rural and urban spaces.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] Generate just and solidarity systems of distribution and commercialization of food.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] Impede monopolistic practices and any type of speculation with food products.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] Supply food to the victims of anthropogenic or natural disasters in risk of accessing food.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] International food donations should not affect health or future production of local food.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] Prevent and protect the population from consuming contaminated food or places their health in risk or if science has uncertainties of its effects.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] Acquire food and primary materials for social and food programs, prioritizing in associative networks of small producers.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] Article 15 protects agricultural, wild and genetic biodiversity by prohibiting genetically modified seeds and crops.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] The President and the National assembly can introduce exceptions, but genetic modification are not allowed if its intervenes with food sovereignty.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] According to Article 364 of the 2008 Constitution of Ecuador, the Ecuadorian state does not see drug consumption as a crime but only as a health concern.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] Since June 2013 the State drugs regulatory office, CONSEP, has published a table that establishes maximum quantities carried by persons so as to be considered in legal possession and that person as not a seller of drugs.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] Within the Ecuadorian Constitution adopted in 2008, Article 67 limits marriage to the union of a man and a woman.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] ("El matrimonio es la unión entre hombre y mujer...") Same-sex couples became eligible for *de facto* civil unions based on Article 68, which specifies that unmarried couples in stable and monogamous unions enjoy the same rights and obligations of married couples.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] In 2015, the civil code was updated to allow for civil unions to be contracted without a requirement for prior cohabitation.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] Article 68 also limits adoption rights to opposite-sex couples.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] In 2019, Ecuador's Constitutional Court legalized same-sex marriage.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] Article 11, paragraph two of the Constitution of the Republic of Ecuador reaffirmed as a fundamental right to sexual orientation and included for the first time and even globally gender identity.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/2008-constitution-of-ecuador] Until 2008, no constitution in the world recognized gender identity.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The word *Ahimsa*—sometimes spelled *Ahinsa*—derives from the Sanskrit root *hiṃs*, meaning to strike; *hiṃsā* is injury or harm, while *a-hiṃsā* (prefixed with the alpha privative), its opposite, is *non-harming* or *nonviolence*.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Reverence for *ahimsa* can be found in Jain, Hindu, and Buddhist canonical texts.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Lord Parshvanatha (the 23rd of Jainism's 24 Tirthankaras) is said to have preached *ahimsa* as one of the four vows.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Scholars describe nonviolence as a central doctrinal and practical principle of Jainism, developed to an extent that distinguishes it from most other religious traditions of the Indian subcontinent.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] 1500 BCE) is the oldest surviving text in India, but many scholars believe the specific ethical practice of *ahimsa* originated in the non-Vedic *Sramana* traditions (which include Jainism and Buddhism) before being absorbed into Brahmanism.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Deshmukh, suggest that the roots of *ahimsa* and asceticism may date to the Indus Valley Civilisation (c.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] 3300–1300 BCE), citing the discovery of seals depicting figures in the *kayotsarga* (standing meditation) posture common to Jain iconography.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Indologist Johannes Bronkhorst has proposed the "Greater Magadha" theory, arguing that the eastern Gangetic plain (modern Bihar/Bengal) developed a distinct non-Vedic culture where concepts like *Karma*, rebirth, and *ahimsa* originated.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] According to this view, the Vedic priesthood later adopted these concepts as they expanded eastward.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Similarly, the German Indologist Ludwig Alsdorf argued that *ahimsa* likely began not as a moral rule but as a "magico-ritualistic" taboo against killing or harming living beings, which was part of a pan-Indian or pre-Aryan heritage later refined into an ethical system by the Jains.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The concept of *ahimsa* evolved gradually within the Vedic tradition.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] 1500–1000 BCE), animal sacrifice was a central component of ritual life.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Then the concept transitioned from a ritualistic concern-avoiding injury to the sacrificer or the minute details of the ritual—to an internalized ethical virtue.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] By the late Vedic era, texts like the *Chandogya Upanishad* (c.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] 8th century BCE) explicitly listed *ahimsa* as one of five essential virtues (along with truthfulness and charity).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The *Yajurveda* reflects this shifting ethos with prayers for universal peace, such as: "May all beings look at me with a friendly eye, may I do likewise, and may we look at each other with the eyes of a friend".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The principle of *ahimsa* moved from personal asceticism to state policy under the Mauryan Emperor Ashoka (c.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Following the Kalinga War, Ashoka renounced military conquest in favor of "conquest by Dharma".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] His Rock Edicts restricted animal slaughter, established medical care for animals, and promoted nonviolence as a civic duty, embedding the Shramanic value of *ahimsa* into India's political fabric.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] In Jainism, the understanding and implementation of *ahimsa* is more radical, scrupulous, and comprehensive than in any other religion.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Killing any living being out of passions like attachment is considered *hiṃsā* (to injure) and abstaining from such an act is *ahimsā* (noninjury).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The vow of *ahimsā* is considered the foremost among the "five vows of Jainism".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Other vows like truth (*satya*) are meant for safeguarding the vow of *ahimsā*.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The statement *ahimsā paramo dharmaḥ* (or, "Non-injury/nonviolence/harmlessness is the supreme/ultimate/paramount/highest/absolute duty/virtue/attribute/religion") is often found inscribed on the walls of the Jain temples.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] As in Hinduism, the aim is to prevent the accumulation of harmful karma.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The Jain concept of *ahimsa* is characterised by detailed classifications of life.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Jains categorize living beings (*jiva*) based on their sensory faculties (*indriyas*), ranging from one-sensed beings (plants, water, earth) to five-sensed beings (humans, animals).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Killing of animals for food is absolutely ruled out.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Jains also make considerable efforts not to injure plants in everyday life as far as possible.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Though they admit that plants must be destroyed for the sake of food, they accept such violence only inasmuch as it is indispensable for human survival, and there are special instructions for preventing unnecessary violence against plants.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Jain monks and nuns go out of their way so as not to hurt even small insects and other minuscule animals.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Both the renouncers and the laypeople of Jain faith reject meat, fish, alcohol, and honey as these are believed to harm large or minuscule life forms.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] In the practice of *ahimsa*, the requirements are less strict for the lay persons (*sravakas*) who have undertaken *anuvrata* (Smaller Vows) than for the Jain monastics who are bound by the Mahavrata "Great Vows".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Jain scholars have debated the potential injury to other life forms during one's occupation.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Certain Jain texts (according to Padmanabh Jaini, a Jainism scholar) forbid people of its faith from husbandry, agriculture, and trade in animal-derived products.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Some Jains abstain from farming because it inevitably entails unintentional killing or injuring of many small animals, such as worms and insects.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] These teachings, in part, have led the Jain community to focus on trade, merchant, clerical, and administrative occupations to minimize *arambhaja-himsa* (occupational violence against all life forms).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] For the layperson, the teaching has been of *ahimsa* with *pramada* – that is, reducing violence through proper intention and being careful in every action on a daily basis to minimize violence to all life forms.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] When Mahavira revived and reorganised the Jain faith in the 6th or 5th century BCE, *ahimsa* was already an established, strictly observed rule.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Rishabhanatha (Ādinātha), the first Jain Tirthankara, whom modern Western historians consider to be a historical figure, followed by Parshvanatha (Pārśvanātha) the twenty-third Tirthankara lived in about the 9th century BCE.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] He founded the community to which Mahavira's parents belonged.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Ahimsa was already part of the "Fourfold Restraint" (*Caujjama*), the vows taken by Parshva's followers.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] In the times of Mahavira and in the following centuries, Jains were at odds with both Buddhists and followers of the Vedic religion or Hindus, whom they accused of negligence and inconsistency in the implementation of *ahimsa*.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] According to the Jain tradition either lacto vegetarianism or veganism is prescribed.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The Jain texts, unlike most Hindu and Buddhist texts on just war, have been inconsistent.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] For its monastic community – *sadhu* and *sadhvi* – the historically accepted practice has been to "willingly sacrifice one's own life" to the attacker, to not retaliate, so that the mendicant may keep the First Great Vow of "total nonviolence".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Jain literature of the 10th century CE, for example, describes a king ready for war and being given lessons about non-violence by the Jain acharya (spiritual teacher).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] In the 12th century CE and thereafter, in an era of violent raids, destruction of temples, the slaughter of agrarian communities and ascetics by Islamic armies, Jain scholars reconsidered the First Great Vow of mendicants and its parallel for the laypeople.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The medieval texts of this era, such as by Jinadatta Suri, recommended both the mendicants and the laypeople to fight and kill if that would prevent greater and continued violence on humans and other life forms (*virodhi-himsa*).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Such exemptions to *ahimsa* is a relatively rare teaching in Jain texts, states Dundas.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Mahatma Gandhi stated, "No religion in the World has explained the principle of *Ahiṃsā* so deeply and systematically as is discussed with its applicability in every human life in Jainism.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] As and when the benevolent principle of *Ahiṃsā* or non-violence will be ascribed for practice by the people of the world to achieve their end of life in this world and beyond, Jainism is sure to have the uppermost status and Mahāvīra is sure to be respected as the greatest authority on *Ahiṃsā*".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The term *Ahimsa* appears in the text Taittiriya Shakha of the Yajurveda (TS 5.2.8.7), where it refers to non-injury to the sacrificer.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] It occurs several times in the *Shatapatha Brahmana* in the sense of "non-injury".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The *Ahimsa* doctrine is a late Vedic era development in Brahmanical culture.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The earliest reference to the idea of nonviolence to animals (*pashu-Ahimsa*), apparently in a moral sense, is in the Kapisthala Katha Samhita of the Yajurveda (KapS 31.11), which may have been written around 1500-1200 BCE.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The Chandogya Upanishad (3.17.4) includes ahimsa in its list of virtues.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] According to John Bowker, the word appears but is uncommon in the principal Upanishads.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Kaneda gives examples of the word *pashu-Ahimsa* in these Upanishads.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Other scholars suggest *Ahimsa* as an ethical concept started evolving in the Vedas, becoming an increasingly central concept in the Upanishads.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The Chāndogya Upaniṣad, dated to 800 to 600 BCE, one of the oldest Upanishads, has the earliest evidence of Vedic use of the word *Ahimsa* in the sense familiar in Hinduism (a code of conduct).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] It bars violence against "all creatures" (*sarvabhuta*), and the practitioner of *Ahimsa* is said to escape the cycle of rebirths (CU 8.15.1).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Some scholars say this mention may have been a Jainist influence on Vedic Hinduism.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Others scholar say that is speculative, and though Jainism is an ancient tradition, the oldest traceable texts of Jainism are from many centuries after the Vedic era ended.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Chāndogya Upaniṣad also names *Ahimsa*, along with *Satyavacanam* (truthfulness), *Ārjavam* (sincerity), *Dānam* (charity), and *Tapo* (penance/meditation), as one of five essential virtues (CU 3.17.4).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The Sandilya Upanishad lists ten forbearances: *Ahimsa*, *Satya*, *Asteya*, *Brahmacharya*, *Daya*, *Arjava*, *Kshama*, *Dhriti*, *Mitahara*, and *Saucha*.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] According to Kaneda, the term *Ahimsa* is an important spiritual doctrine shared by Hinduism, Buddhism, and Jainism.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] It means 'non-injury' and 'non-killing'.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] It implies total avoidance of harming any living creature by deeds, words, or thoughts.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The Hindu epic the Mahabharata repeatedly uses the phrase *Ahimsa Paramo Dharma* (अहिंसा परमॊ धर्मः), which literally means "nonviolence is the highest moral virtue".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The phrase *Ahimsa Paramo Dharma* also appears in Adi Parva, Vana Parva, and Anushasana Parva.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The Bhagavad Gita discusses doubts and questions about appropriate response when one faces systematic violence or war.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] These verses develop the concepts of lawful violence in self-defence and just war theory.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] But there is no consensus on this interpretation.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Gandhi, for example, considered this debate about nonviolence and lawful violence a mere metaphor for the war within a human being when they face moral questions.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The classical texts of Hinduism devote numerous chapters to discussing what people who practice the virtue of *ahimsa* can and must do when faced with war, violent threat, or the need to sentence someone convicted of a crime.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] These discussions have led to theories of just war, ideas of reasonable self-defense, and views of proportionate punishment.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Arthashastra discusses, among other things, what constitutes proportionate response and punishment.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The precepts of *ahimsa* in Hinduism require that war must be avoided, with sincere and truthful dialogue.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] If war becomes necessary, its cause must be just, its purpose virtuous, its objective to restrain the wicked, its aim peace, and its method lawful.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] War may be started and stopped only by a legitimate authority.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Weapons must be proportionate to the opponent and the goal, not indiscriminate tools of destruction.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] All strategies and weapons used in war must be to defeat the opponent, not to cause them misery; for example, arrows are allowed, but arrows smeared with painful poison are not.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Warriors must use judgment in the battlefield.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Wounded, unarmed opponents must not be attacked or killed but instead given medical care.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Children, women, and civilians must not be injured.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] While the war is in progress, sincere dialogue for peace must continue.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Different interpretations of ancient Hindu texts have been offered in matters of self-defense.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] For example, Tähtinen suggests self-defense is appropriate, criminals are not protected by the rule of *ahimsa*, and Hindu scriptures support violence against an armed attacker.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] *ahimsa* is not meant to imply pacifism.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Alternative theories of self-defense, inspired by *ahimsa*, build principles similar to ideas of just war.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Aikido, pioneered in Japan, illustrates one such set of principles for self-defense.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Morihei Ueshiba, the founder of Aikido, described his inspiration as Ahimsa.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] According to this interpretation of *ahimsa* in self-defense, one must not assume that the world is free of aggression.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] One must presume that some people will, out of ignorance, error, or fear, attack others or intrude into their space, physically or verbally.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The aim of self-defense, suggested Ueshiba, must be to neutralize the attacker's aggression and avoid conflict.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The best defense is one with which the victim is protected and the attacker is respected and not injured if possible.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Under *ahimsa* and Aikido, there are no enemies, and appropriate self-defense focuses on neutralizing the immaturity, assumptions, and aggressive strivings of the attacker.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Tähtinen concludes that Hindus have no misgivings about the death penalty; their position is that evil-doers who deserve death should be killed and that a king, in particular, is obliged to punish criminals and should not hesitate to kill them, even if they happen to be his brothers and sons.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Other scholars conclude that Hindu scriptures suggest that sentences for any crime must be fair, proportional, and not cruel.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The Hindu precept of "cause no injury" applies to animals and all life forms.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] This precept is not found in the oldest verses of Vedas (1500–1000 BCE), but increasingly becomes one of the central ideas in post-Vedic period.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] In the oldest layer of the Vedas, such as the *Rigveda*, ritual sacrifices of animals and cooking of meat to feed guests are mentioned.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] This included goat, ox, horse, and others.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] However, the text is not uniform in its prescriptions.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Some verses praise meat as food, while other verses in the Vedas recommend "abstention from meat", in particular, "beef".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] According to Marvin Harris, the Vedic literature is inconsistent, with some verses suggesting ritual slaughter and meat consumption, while others suggesting a taboo on meat-eating.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The late Vedic-era literature (pre-500 BCE) condemns all killings of men, cattle, birds, and horses, and prays to god Agni to punish those who kill.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Later texts of Hinduism declare *ahimsa* as one of the primary virtues, declare any killing or harming any life as against *dharma* (moral life).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The Mahabharata permits hunting by warriors, but opposes it in the case of hermits who must be strictly non-violent.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Across the texts of Hinduism, there is a profusion of ideas about the virtue of *ahimsa* when applied to non-human life, but without a universal consensus.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Alsdorf claims the debate and disagreements between supporters of vegetarian lifestyle and meat eaters was significant.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Even suggested exceptions – ritual slaughter and hunting – were challenged by advocates of *ahimsa*.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] In the Mahabharata both sides present various arguments to substantiate their viewpoints.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Moreover, a hunter defends his profession in a long discourse.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Many of the arguments proposed in favor of non-violence to animals refer to the bliss one feels, the rewards it entails before or after death, the danger and harm it prevents, as well as to the karmic consequences of violence.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The ancient Hindu texts discuss *ahimsa* and non-animal life.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] They discourage wanton destruction of nature including of wild and cultivated plants.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Hermits (sannyasins) were urged to live on a fruitarian diet so as to avoid the destruction of plants.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Scholars claim the principles of ecological nonviolence are innate in the Hindu tradition, and its conceptual fountain has been *ahimsa* as its cardinal virtue.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The classical literature of the Indian religions, such as Hinduism and Jainism, exists in many Indian languages.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] For example, the *Tirukkural,* written in three volumes, likely between 450 and 500 CE, dedicates verses 251–260 and 321–333 of its first volume to the virtue of *ahimsa*, emphasizing on moral vegetarianism and non-killing (*kollamai*).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] However, the *Tirukkural* also glorifies soldiers and their valour during war, and states that it is king's duty to punish criminals and implement "death sentence for the wicked".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Jay Dinshah founded the American Vegan Society (AVS), linking veganism to the concept of *ahimsa*.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] In the 19th and 20th centuries, prominent figures of Indian spirituality such as Shrimad Rajchandra and Swami Vivekananda emphasised the importance of Ahimsa.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Mohandas Karamchand Gandhi successfully promoted the principle of *ahimsa* to all spheres of life, in particular to politics (*Swaraj*).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] His non-violent resistance movement *satyagraha* had an immense impact on India, impressed public opinion in Western countries, and influenced the leaders of various civil and political rights movements such as the American civil rights movement's Martin Luther King Jr. and James Bevel.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] In Gandhi's thought, *ahimsa* precludes not only the act of inflicting a physical injury but also mental states like evil thoughts and hatred, and unkind behavior such as harsh words, dishonesty, and lying, all of which he saw as manifestations of violence incompatible with *ahimsa*.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Gandhi believed *ahimsa* to be a creative energy force, encompassing all interactions leading one's self to find *satya*, "Divine Truth".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Sri Aurobindo criticized the Gandhian concept of *ahimsa* as unrealistic and not universally applicable, noting that while it is a spiritual truth, it should not be applied as a "rigid ethical rule" to all of humanity.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] He adopted a pragmatic non-pacifist position, holding that the justification of violence depends on the specific circumstances and the "dharma" (duty/righteousness) of the situation.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] While he advocated passive resistance as a political policy for India's independence, he maintained that a nation is entitled to use violence for its self-preservation if necessary.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Gandhi took the religious principle of *ahimsa,* and turned it into a non-violent tool for mass action.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] He used it to fight not only colonial rule, but social evils such as racial discrimination and untouchability as well.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Studying *ahimsa*'s history and philosophy influenced Albert Schweitzer's principle of "reverence for life".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] He commended Indian traditions for their ethics of *ahimsa*, considering the prohibition against killing and harming "one of the greatest events in the spiritual history of humankind".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] However, he noted that "not-killing" and "not-harming" might be unfeasible in certain situations, like self-defense, or ethically complex, as in cases of prolonged famine.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] In Buddhist texts *ahimsa* (or its Pāli cognate *avihiṃsā*) is part of the Five Precepts (*Pañcasīla*), the first of which has been to abstain from killing.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] This precept of *ahimsa* is applicable to both the Buddhist layperson and the monastic community.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The *ahimsa* precept is not a commandment, and transgressions did not invite religious sanctions for laypersons, but their power has been in the Buddhist belief in karmic consequences and their impact in afterlife during rebirth.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Killing, in Buddhist belief, could lead to rebirth in the hellish realm, and for a longer time in more severe conditions if the murder victim was a monk.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Saving animals from slaughter for meat is believed to be a way to acquire merit for better rebirth.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] These moral precepts have been voluntarily self-enforced in lay Buddhist culture through the associated belief in karma and rebirth.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Unlike with lay Buddhists, transgressions by monks do invite sanctions.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Full expulsion of a monk from *sangha* follows instances of killing, just like any other serious offense against the monastic *nikaya* code of conduct.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Violent ways of punishing criminals and prisoners of war were not explicitly condemned in Buddhism, but peaceful ways of conflict resolution and punishment with the least amount of injury were encouraged.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The early texts condemn the mental states that lead to violent behavior.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Nonviolence is an overarching theme within the Pāli Canon.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] While the early texts condemn killing in the strongest terms, and portray the ideal ruler as a pacifist, such a ruler is nonetheless flanked by an army.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] It seems that the Buddha's teaching on nonviolence was not interpreted or put into practice in an uncompromisingly pacifist or anti-military service way by early Buddhists.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The early texts assume war to be a fact of life, and well-skilled soldiers are viewed as necessary for defensive warfare.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] In Pali texts, injunctions to abstain from violence and involvement with military affairs are directed at members of the *sangha*; later Mahayana texts, which often generalise monastic norms to laity, require this of lay people as well.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The early texts do not contain just-war ideology as such.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Some argue that a *sutta* in the *Gamani Samyuttam* rules out all military service.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] In this passage, a soldier asks the Buddha if it is true that, as he has been told, soldiers slain in battle are reborn in a heavenly realm.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The Buddha reluctantly replies that if he is killed in battle while his mind is seized with the intention to kill, he will undergo an unpleasant rebirth.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] In the early texts, a person's mental state at the time of death is generally viewed as having a great impact on the next birth.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Some Buddhists point to other early texts as justifying defensive war.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] One example is the *Kosala Samyutta*, in which King Pasenadi of Kosala, a righteous king favored by the Buddha, learns of an impending attack on his kingdom.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] He arms himself in defence, and leads his army into battle to protect his kingdom from attack.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] King Pasenadi eventually defeated Emperor Ajātasattu and captured him alive.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] He thought that, although this King of Magadha has transgressed against his kingdom, he had not transgressed against him personally, and Ajātasattu was still his nephew.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] He released Ajātasattu and did not harm him.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Upon his return, the Buddha said (among other things) that Pasenadi "is a friend of virtue, acquainted with virtue, intimate with virtue", while the opposite is said of the aggressor, King Ajātasattu.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] According to Theravada commentaries, there are five requisite factors that must all be fulfilled for an act to be both an act of killing and to be karmically negative.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] These are: (1) the presence of a living being, human or animal; (2) the knowledge that the being is a living being; (3) the intent to kill; (4) the act of killing by some means; and (5) the resulting death.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Some Buddhists have argued on this basis that the act of killing is complicated, and its ethicality is predicated upon intent.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Some have argued that in defensive postures, for example, the primary intention of a soldier is not to kill, but to defend against aggression, and the act of killing in that situation would have minimal negative karmic repercussions.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] According to Babasaheb Ambedkar, there is circumstantial evidence encouraging *ahimsa* from the Buddha's doctrine, "Love all, so that you may not wish to kill any." Gautama Buddha distinguished between a principle and a rule.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] He did not make *ahimsa* a matter of rule, but suggested it as a matter of principle.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Maurya Emperor Ashoka banned animal sacrifice, hunting, slaughter of "all four-footed creatures that are neither useful nor edible" and specific animal species, female goats, sheep and pigs nursing their young as well as their young up to the age of six months.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Fishing was banned during Chaturmasya and Uposatha.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Slave trade in the Maurya Empire was also banned by Ashoka.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] The emperors of the Sui dynasty, Tang dynasty, and early Song dynasty banned killing in the Lunar calendar's 1st, 5th, and 9th months.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Empress Wu Tse-Tien banned killing for more than half a year in 692.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] Some rulers banned fishing for a period of time each year.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ahimsa] People avoid killing during some festivals, like the Taoist Ghost Festival, the Nine Emperor Gods Festival, and the Vegetarian Festival, as well as during others.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] He received the 1952 Nobel Peace Prize for his philosophy of "Reverence for Life".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] His philosophy was expressed in many ways, but most famously in founding and sustaining the Hôpital Albert Schweitzer in Lambaréné, French Equatorial Africa (now Gabon).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] As a music scholar and organist, he studied the music of German composer Johann Sebastian Bach and influenced the Organ Reform Movement (*Orgelbewegung*).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer was born on 14 January 1875 in Kaysersberg in Alsace, in what had less than four years previously become the Imperial Territory of Alsace-Lorraine in the German Empire.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] He later became a citizen of France after World War I, when Alsace became French territory again.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] He was the son of Adèle (née Schillinger) and Louis Théophile Schweitzer.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] He spent his childhood in Gunsbach, also in Alsace, where his father, the local Lutheran-Evangelical pastor of the EPCAAL, taught him how to play music.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] The tiny village would become home to the Association Internationale Albert Schweitzer (AIAS).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] The medieval parish church of Gunsbach was shared by the Protestant and Catholic congregations, which held their prayers in different areas at different times on Sundays.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] This compromise arose after the Protestant Reformation and the Thirty Years' War.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer, the pastor's son, grew up in this exceptional environment of religious tolerance, and developed the belief that true Christianity should always work towards a unity of faith and purpose.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer's first language was the Alsatian dialect of German.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] At the Mulhouse gymnasium he received his "Abitur" (the certificate at the end of secondary education) in 1893.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] He studied organ in Mulhouse from 1885 to 1893 with Eugène Munch, organist at the Protestant cathedral, who inspired Schweitzer with his enthusiasm for the music of German composer Richard Wagner.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] In 1893, he played for the French organist Charles-Marie Widor (at Saint-Sulpice, Paris), for whom Johann Sebastian Bach's organ music contained a mystic sense of the eternal.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Widor, deeply impressed, agreed to teach Schweitzer without fee, and a great and influential friendship thus began.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] From 1893 Schweitzer studied Protestant theology at the Kaiser Wilhelm University in Strasbourg.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] There he also received instruction in piano and counterpoint from professor Gustav Jacobsthal, and associated closely with Ernest Munch, the brother of his former teacher, organist of St William church, who was also a passionate admirer of J.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer served his one-year compulsory military service in 1894.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer saw many operas of Richard Wagner in Strasbourg under Otto Lohse, and in 1896 he managed to afford a visit to the Bayreuth Festival to see Wagner's *Der Ring des Nibelungen* and *Parsifal*, both of which impressed him.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] In 1898, he returned to Paris to write a PhD dissertation on *The Religious Philosophy of Kant* at the Sorbonne, and to study in earnest with Widor.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Here he often met with the elderly Aristide Cavaillé-Coll.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] He also studied piano at that time with Marie Jaëll.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] In 1899, Schweitzer spent the summer semester at the University of Berlin and eventually obtained his theology degree at the University of Strasbourg.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] He published his PhD thesis at the University of Tübingen in 1899.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] In 1905, Schweitzer began his study of medicine at the University of Strasbourg, culminating in the degree of M.D. in 1913.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer rapidly gained prominence as a musical scholar and organist, dedicated also to the rescue, restoration and study of historic pipe organs.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] With theological insight, he interpreted the use of pictorial and symbolical representation in J.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] In 1899, he astonished Widor by explaining figures and motifs in Bach's Chorale Preludes as painter-like tonal and rhythmic imagery illustrating themes from the words of the hymns on which they were based.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] They were works of devotional contemplation in which the musical design corresponded to literary ideas, conceived visually.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Widor had not grown up with knowledge of the old Lutheran hymns.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] The exposition of these ideas, encouraged by Widor and Munch, became Schweitzer's last task, and appeared in the masterly study *J.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Bach: Le Musicien-Poète*, written in French and published in 1905.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] There was great demand for a German edition, but, instead of translating it, he decided to rewrite it.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Bach*), which were published in 1908 and translated into English by Ernest Newman in 1911.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Ernst Cassirer, a contemporaneous German philosopher, called it "one of the best interpretations" of Bach.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] During its preparation, Schweitzer became a friend of Cosima Wagner, then resident in Strasbourg, with whom he had many theological and musical conversations, exploring his view of Bach's descriptive music, and playing the major Chorale Preludes for her at the Temple Neuf.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer's interpretative approach greatly influenced the modern understanding of Bach's music.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] He became a welcome guest at the Wagners' home, Wahnfried.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] He also corresponded with composer Clara Faisst, who became a good friend.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] In 1909, he addressed the *Third Congress of the International Society of Music* at Vienna on the subject.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Having circulated a questionnaire among players and organ-builders in several European countries, he produced a very considered report.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] This provided the basis for the *International Regulations for Organ Building*.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer also studied piano under Isidor Philipp, head of the piano department at the Paris Conservatory.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] In 1905, Widor and Schweitzer were among the six musicians who founded the Paris Bach Society, a choir dedicated to performing J.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Bach's music, for whose concerts Schweitzer took the organ part regularly until 1913.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] He was also appointed organist for the Bach Concerts of the Orféo Català at Barcelona, Spain, and often travelled there for that purpose.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] He and Widor collaborated on a new edition of Bach's organ works, with detailed analysis of each work in English, French, and German.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer, who insisted that the score should show Bach's notation with no additional markings, wrote the commentaries for the Preludes and Fugues, and Widor those for the Sonatas and Concertos: six volumes were published in 1912–14.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Three more, to contain the Chorale Preludes with Schweitzer's analyses, were to be worked on in Africa, but these were never completed, perhaps because for him they were inseparable from his evolving theological thought.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] On departure for Lambaréné in 1913, he was presented with a pedal piano, a piano with pedal attachments to operate like an organ pedal-keyboard.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Built especially for the tropics, it was delivered by river in a huge dug-out canoe to Lambaréné, packed in a zinc-lined case.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] At first, he regarded his new life as a renunciation of his art, and fell out of practice, but after some time he resolved to study and learn by heart the works of Bach, Mendelssohn, Widor, César Franck, and Max Reger systematically.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] It became his custom to play during the lunch hour and on Sunday afternoons.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer's pedal piano was still in use at Lambaréné in 1946.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Gaine Cannon, of Balsam Grove, N.C., the old, dilapidated piano-organ was still being played by Dr.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer in 1962, and stories told that "his fingers were still lively" on the old instrument at 88 years of age.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Sir Donald Tovey dedicated his conjectural completion of Bach's *The Art of Fugue* to Schweitzer.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer's recordings of organ music, and his innovative recording technique, are described below.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] One of his pupils was conductor and composer Hans Münch.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] In 1899, Schweitzer became a deacon at the church of Saint Nicholas in Strasbourg.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] In 1900, with the completion of his licentiate in theology, he was ordained as priest, and that year he witnessed the Oberammergau Passion Play.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] In the following year, he became provisional Principal of the Theological College of Saint Thomas, from which he had just graduated, and in 1903 his appointment was made permanent.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] In 1906, he published *Geschichte der Leben-Jesu-Forschung* (History of Life-of-Jesus research).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] This book, which established his reputation, was first published in English in 1910 as *The Quest of the Historical Jesus*.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Under this title the book became famous in the English-speaking world.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] A second German edition was published in 1913, containing theologically significant revisions and expansions: this revised edition did not appear in English until 2001.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] In 1931, he published *Mystik des Apostels Paulus* (*The Mysticism of Paul the Apostle*).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] In *The Quest*, Schweitzer criticised the liberal view put forward by liberal and romantic scholars during the first quest for the historical Jesus.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer maintained that the life of Jesus must be interpreted in the light of Jesus' own convictions, which reflected late Jewish eschatology and apocalypticism.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Instead of these liberal and romantic views, Schweitzer wrote that Jesus and his followers expected the imminent end of the world.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer cross-referenced the many New Testament verses declaring imminent fulfilment of the promise of the World's ending within the lifetime of Jesus's original followers.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] "This generation shall not pass, till all these things be fulfilled" (Matthew, 24:34) or, "have taken place" (Luke 21:32).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Similarly, in 1st Peter 1:20, "Christ, who verily was foreordained before the foundation of the world but was manifest in these last times for you", as well as "But the end of all things is at hand" (1 Peter 4:7) and "Surely, I come quickly." (Revelation 22:20).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Either Jesus, his disciples and/or the noted chapter authors were and remain seriously mistaken; the promised second return timeframe has long ago passed.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] In *The Mysticism of Paul the Apostle*, Schweitzer first distinguishes between two categories of mysticism: primitive and developed.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Primitive mysticism "has not yet risen to a conception of the universal, and is still confined to naive views of earthly and super-earthly, temporal and eternal".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Additionally, he argues that this view of a "union with the divinity, brought about by efficacious ceremonies, is found even in quite primitive religions".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] On the other hand, a more developed form of mysticism can be found in the Greek mystery-cults that were popular in first-century A.D. society.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] These included the cults of Attis, Osiris, and Mithras.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] A developed form of mysticism is attained when the "conception of the universal is reached and a man reflects upon his relation to the totality of being and to Being in itself".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer claims that this form of mysticism is more intellectual and can be found "among the Brahmans and in the Buddha, in Platonism, in Stoicism, in Spinoza, Schopenhauer, and Hegel".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Next, Schweitzer poses the question: "Of what precise kind then is the mysticism of Paul?" He locates Paul between the two extremes of primitive mysticism and developed mysticism.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Paul stands high above primitive mysticism, due to his intellectual writings, but never speaks of being one with God or being in God.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Instead, he conceives of sonship to God as "mediated and effected by means of the mystical union with Christ".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] He summarizes Pauline mysticism as "being in Christ" rather than "being in God".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Paul's imminent eschatology, from his background in Jewish eschatology, causes him to believe that the kingdom of God has not yet come and that Christians are now living in the time of Christ.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Christ-mysticism holds the field until God-mysticism becomes possible, which is in the near future.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Therefore, Schweitzer argues that Paul is the only theologian who does not claim that Christians can have an experience of "being-in-God".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Rather, Paul uses the phrase "being-in-Christ" to illustrate how Jesus is a mediator between the Christian community and God.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Additionally, Schweitzer explains how the experience of "being-in-Christ" is not a "static partaking in the spiritual being of Christ, but as the real co-experiencing of His dying and rising again".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] The "realistic" partaking in the mystery of Jesus is only possible within the solidarity of the Christian community.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] One of Schweitzer's major arguments in *The Mysticism of Paul the Apostle* is that Paul's mysticism, marked by his phrase "being in Christ", gives the clue to the whole of Pauline theology.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Rather than reading justification by faith as the main topic of Pauline thought, which has been the most popular argument set forward by Martin Luther, Schweitzer argues that Paul's emphasis was on the mystical union with God by "being in Christ".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer contrasts Paul's "realistic" dying and rising with Christ to the "symbolism" of Hellenism.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Although Paul is widely influenced by Hellenistic thought, he is not controlled by it.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer explains that Paul focused on the idea of fellowship with the divine being through the "realistic" dying and rising with Christ rather than the "symbolic" Hellenistic act of becoming like Christ through deification.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] After baptism, Christians are continually renewed throughout their lifetimes due to participation in the dying and rising with Christ (most notably through the Sacraments).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] On the other hand, the Hellenist "lives on the store of experience which he acquired in the initiation" and is not continually affected by a shared communal experience.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Another major difference between Paul's "realism" and Hellenistic "symbolism" is the exclusive nature of the former and the inclusive nature of the latter.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer unabashedly emphasizes the fact that "Paul's thought follows predestinarian lines".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] He explains, "only the man who is elected thereto can enter into relation with God".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Although every human being is invited to become a Christian, only those who have undergone the initiation into the Christian community through baptism can share in the "realistic" dying and rising with Christ.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] At the age of 30, in 1905, Schweitzer answered the call of The Society of the Evangelist Missions of Paris, which was looking for a physician.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] The committee of this missionary society was not ready to accept his offer, considering his Lutheran theology to be "incorrect".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] He could easily have obtained a place in a German evangelical mission, but wished to follow the original call despite the doctrinal difficulties.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Amid a hail of protests from his friends, family and colleagues, he resigned from his post and re-entered the university as a student in a three-year course towards the degree of Doctorate in Medicine, a subject in which he had little knowledge or previous aptitude.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] He planned to spread the Gospel by the example of his Christian labour of healing, rather than through the verbal process of preaching, and believed that this service should be acceptable within any branch of Christian teaching.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Even in his study of medicine, and through his clinical course, Schweitzer pursued the ideal of the philosopher-scientist.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] He completed his studies successfully at the end of 1911.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] His medical degree dissertation was another work on the historical Jesus, *Die psychiatrische Beurteilung Jesu.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Darstellung und Kritik* (The psychiatric evaluation of Jesus.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Description and criticism), published in English in 1948 as *The Psychiatric Study of Jesus.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] In June 1912, he married Helene Bresslau, municipal inspector for orphans and daughter of the Jewish pan-Germanist historian Harry Bresslau.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] In 1912, now armed with a medical degree, Schweitzer made a definite proposal to go as a physician to work at his own expense in the Paris Missionary Society's mission at Lambaréné on the Ogooué river, in what is now Gabon, in Africa, then a French colony.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] He refused to attend a committee to inquire into his doctrine, but met each committee member personally and was at last accepted.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Through concerts and other fund-raising, he was ready to equip a small hospital.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] In early 1913, he and his wife set off to establish a hospital, the Hôpital Albert Schweitzer, near an existing mission post.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] The site was nearly 200 miles, 14 days by raft, upstream from the mouth of the Ogooué at Port Gentil (Cape Lopez).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] It was accessible to external communications, but downstream of most tributaries, so that internal communications within Gabon converged towards Lambaréné.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] In the first nine months, he and his wife had about 2,000 patients to examine, some travelling many days and hundreds of kilometres to reach him.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer's wife, Helene Schweitzer, served as an anaesthetist for surgical operations.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] After briefly occupying a shed formerly used as a chicken hut, in late 1913 they built their first hospital of corrugated iron, with a consulting room and operating theatre and with a dispensary and sterilising room.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] The waiting room and dormitory were built, like native huts, of unhewn logs along a path leading to the boat landing.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] The Schweitzers had their own bungalow and employed as their assistant Joseph, a French-speaking Mpongwe, who first came to Lambaréné as a patient.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] After World War I broke out in July 1914, Schweitzer and his wife, German citizens in a French colony when the countries were at war, were put under supervision by the French military at Lambaréné, where Schweitzer continued his work.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] In 1917, exhausted by over four years' work and by tropical anaemia, they were taken to Bordeaux and interned first in Garaison and then from March 1918 in Saint-Rémy-de-Provence.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] In July 1918, after being transferred to his home in Alsace, he was a free man again.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] At this time Schweitzer, born a German citizen, had his parents' former pre-1871 French citizenship reinstated, and became a French citizen.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Working as a medical assistant and assistant-pastor in Strasbourg, he advanced his project on the philosophy of civilization, which had occupied his mind since 1900.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] By 1920, his health recovering, he was giving organ recitals and doing other fund-raising work to repay borrowings and raise funds for returning to Gabon.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] In 1922, he delivered the Dale Memorial Lectures in the University of Oxford, and from these in the following year appeared Volumes I and II of his great work, *The Decay and Restoration of Civilization* and *Civilization and Ethics*.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] The two remaining volumes, on *The World-View of Reverence for Life* and a fourth on the Civilized State, were never completed.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] In 1924, Schweitzer returned to Africa without his wife, but with an Oxford undergraduate, Noel Gillespie, as his assistant.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Everything was heavily decayed, and building and doctoring progressed together for months.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] He now had salvarsan for treating syphilitic ulcers and framboesia.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Additional medical staff, nurse (Miss) Kottmann and Dr.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Victor Nessmann, joined him in 1924, and Dr.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Mark Lauterberg in 1925; the growing hospital was staffed by native orderlies.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Trensz replaced Nessmann, and Martha Lauterberg and Hans Muggenstorm joined them.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] In 1925–6, new hospital buildings were constructed, and also a ward for white patients, so that the site became like a village.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] The onset of famine and a dysentery epidemic created fresh problems.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Much of the building work was carried out with the help of local people and patients.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Drug advances for sleeping sickness included Germanin and tryparsamide.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Trensz conducted experiments showing that the non-amoebic strain of dysentery was caused by a paracholera vibrion (facultative anaerobic bacteria).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] With the new hospital built and the medical team established, Schweitzer returned to Europe in 1927, this time leaving a functioning hospital at work.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Gradually his opinions and concepts became acknowledged, not only in Europe, but worldwide.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] There was a further period of work in 1935.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] In January 1937, he returned to Lambaréné and continued working there throughout World War II.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] In 1953, the journalist James Cameron visited Lambaréné, when Schweitzer was 78, and found significant flaws in the practices and attitudes of Schweitzer and his staff.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] The hospital suffered from squalor and was without modern amenities, and Schweitzer had little contact with the local people.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Cameron did not make public what he had seen at the time: according to a BBC dramatisation, he made the unusual journalistic decision to withhold the story, and resisted the expressed wish of his employers to publish an exposé.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer's biographer Edgar Berman, who was a volunteer surgeon at Lambarene for several months and had extended conversations with Schweitzer, has a different perspective.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer felt that patients were better off, and the hospital functioned better given the severe lack of funding, if patients' families lived on the hospital grounds during treatment.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Surgical survival rates were, Berman asserts, as high as in many fully equipped western hospitals.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] The volume of patients needing care, the difficulty of obtaining materials and supplies, and the scarcity of trained medical staff willing to work long hours in the remote setting for almost no pay all argued for a spartan setting with an emphasis on high medical standards nevertheless.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer considered his work as a medical missionary in Africa to be his response to Jesus' call to become "fishers of men".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer was one of colonialism's harshest critics.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer was nonetheless still sometimes accused of being paternalistic in his attitude towards Africans.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] For instance, he thought that Gabonese independence came too early, without adequate education or accommodation to local circumstances.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer eventually emended and complicated this notion with his later statement that "The time for speaking of older and younger brothers has passed".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] American journalist John Gunther visited Lambaréné in the 1950s and reported Schweitzer's patronizing attitude towards Africans.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] He also noted the lack of Africans trained to be skilled workers.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] By comparison, his English contemporary Albert Ruskin Cook in Uganda had been training nurses and midwives since the 1910s, and had published a manual of midwifery in the local language of Luganda.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] After three decades in Africa, Schweitzer still depended on Europe for nurses.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] The keynote of Schweitzer's personal philosophy, which he considered to be his greatest contribution to mankind, was the idea of *Reverence for Life* (*Ehrfurcht vor dem Leben*).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] He thought that Western civilization was decaying because it had abandoned affirmation of life as its ethical foundation.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] In the Preface to *Civilization and Ethics* (1923) he argued that Western philosophy from Descartes to Kant had set out to explain the objective world expecting that humanity would be found to have a special meaning within it.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] But no such meaning was found, and the rational, life-affirming optimism of the Age of Enlightenment began to evaporate.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] A rift opened between this world-view, as material knowledge, and the life-view, understood as Will, expressed in the pessimist philosophies from Schopenhauer onward.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Scientific materialism, advanced by Herbert Spencer and Charles Darwin, portrayed an objective world process devoid of ethics, entirely an expression of the will-to-live.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer wrote, "True philosophy must start from the most immediate and comprehensive fact of consciousness, and this may be formulated as follows: 'I am life which wills to live, and i exist in the midst of life which wills to live.'" In nature one form of life must always prey upon another.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] However, human consciousness holds an awareness of, and sympathy for, the will of other beings to live.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] An ethical human strives to escape from this contradiction so far as possible.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Though we cannot perfect the endeavour we should strive for it: the will-to-live constantly renews itself, for it is both an evolutionary necessity and a spiritual phenomenon.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Life and love are rooted in this same principle, in a personal spiritual relationship to the universe.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Ethics themselves proceed from the need to respect the wish of other beings to exist as one does towards oneself.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Even so, Schweitzer found many instances in world religions and philosophies in which the principle was denied, not least in the European Middle Ages, and in the Indian Brahminic philosophy.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] For Schweitzer, mankind had to accept that objective reality is ethically neutral.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] It could then affirm a new Enlightenment through spiritual rationalism, by giving priority to volition or ethical will as the primary meaning of life.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Mankind had to choose to create the moral structures of civilization: the worldview must derive from the life-view, not vice versa.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Respect for life, overcoming coarser impulses and hollow doctrines, leads the individual to live in the service of other people and of every living creature.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] In contemplation of the will-to-life, respect for the life of others becomes the highest principle and the defining purpose of humanity.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Such was the theory which Schweitzer sought to put into practice in his own life.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] According to some authors, Schweitzer's thought, and specifically his development of reverence for life, was influenced by Indian religious thought and in particular the Jain principle of ahimsa, or non-violence.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Further on ahimsa and the reverence for life in the same book, he elaborates on the ancient Indian didactic work of the Tirukkural, which he observed that, like the Buddha and the Bhagavad Gita, "stands for the commandment not to kill and not to damage".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] "There are two means of refuge from the miseries of life: music and cats" he stated.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] After the birth of their daughter (Rhena Schweitzer Miller), Albert's wife, Helene Schweitzer was no longer able to live in Lambaréné due to her health.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] In 1923, the family moved to Königsfeld im Schwarzwald, Baden-Württemberg, where he was building a house for the family.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] This house is now maintained as a Schweitzer museum.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] From 1939 to 1948, he stayed in Lambaréné, unable to return to Europe because of the war.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Three years after the end of World War II, in 1948, he returned for the first time to Europe and kept travelling back and forth (and once to the US) as long as he was able.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] During his return visits to his home village of Gunsbach, Schweitzer continued to use the family house, which after his death became an archive and museum of his life and work.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] His life was portrayed in the 1952 movie *Il est minuit, Docteur Schweitzer*, starring Pierre Fresnay as Albert Schweitzer and Jeanne Moreau as his nurse Marie.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer inspired actor Hugh O'Brian when O'Brian visited in Africa.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] O'Brian returned to the United States and founded the Hugh O'Brian Youth Leadership Foundation (HOBY).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize of 1952, accepting the prize with the speech, "The Problem of Peace".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] With the $33,000 prize money, he started the leprosarium at Lambaréné.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] From 1952 until his death he worked against nuclear tests and nuclear weapons with Albert Einstein, Otto Hahn and Bertrand Russell.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] In 1957 and 1958, he broadcast four speeches over Radio Oslo, which were published in *Peace or Atomic War*.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] In 1957, Schweitzer was one of the founders of The Committee for a Sane Nuclear Policy.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] On 23 April 1957, Schweitzer made his "Declaration of Conscience" speech; it was broadcast to the world over Radio Oslo, pleading for the abolition of nuclear weapons.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Weeks prior to his death, an American film crew was allowed to visit Schweitzer and Drs.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Muntz and Friedman, both Holocaust survivors, to record his work and daily life at the hospital.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] The film *The Legacy of Albert Schweitzer*, narrated by Henry Fonda, was produced by Warner Brothers and aired once.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] It resides in their vault today in deteriorating condition.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Although several attempts have been made to restore and re-air the film, all access has been denied.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] In 1955, he was made an honorary member of the Order of Merit (OM) by Queen Elizabeth II.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] He was also a chevalier of the Military and Hospitaller Order of Saint Lazarus of Jerusalem.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer died on 4 September 1965 at his beloved hospital in Lambaréné, now in independent Gabon.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] His grave, on the banks of the Ogooué River, is marked by a cross he made himself.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] His cousin Anne-Marie Schweitzer Sartre was the mother of Jean-Paul Sartre.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Her father, Charles Schweitzer, was the older brother of Albert Schweitzer's father, Louis Théophile.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer is often cited in vegetarian literature as being an advocate of vegetarianism in his later years.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer was not a vegetarian in his earlier life.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] For example, in 1950, biographer Magnus C.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Ratter commented that Schweitzer never "commit[ted] himself to the anti-vivisection, vegetarian, or pacifist positions, though his thought leads in this direction".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Biographer James Bentley has written that Schweitzer became a vegetarian after his wife's death in 1957 and he was "living almost entirely on lentil soup".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Stamos has written that Schweitzer was not a vegetarian in his personal life nor imposed it on his missionary hospital, but he did help animals and was opposed to hunting.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Stamos noted that Schweitzer held the view that evolution ingrained humans with an instinct for meat, so it was useless in trying to deny it.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] The *Albert Schweitzer Fellowship* was founded in 1940 by Schweitzer to unite US supporters in filling the gap in support for his Hospital when his European supply lines were cut off by war, and continues to support the Lambaréné Hospital today.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer considered his ethic of Reverence for Life, not his hospital, his most important legacy, saying that his Lambaréné Hospital was just "my own improvisation on the theme of Reverence for Life.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Today, the ASF helps large numbers of young Americans in health-related professional fields find or create "their own Lambaréné" in the US or internationally.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] ASF selects and supports nearly 250 new US and Africa Schweitzer Fellows each year from over 100 of the leading US schools of medicine, nursing, public health, and every other field with some relation to health, including music, law, and divinity.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] The peer-supporting lifelong network of "Schweitzer Fellows for Life" numbered over 2,000 members in 2008, and is growing by nearly 1,000 every four years.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Nearly 150 of these Schweitzer Fellows have served at the Hospital in Lambaréné, for three-month periods during their last year of medical school.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] Schweitzer's writings and life are often quoted, resulting in a number of eponyms, such as the 'Schweitzer technique' (discussed below), and the 'Schweitzer effect'.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] The 'Schweitzer effect' refers to his statement that 'Example is not the main thing in influencing others; it is the only thing'.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p01] This eponym is used in medical education to highlight the relationship between lived experience/example and medical students' opinions on professional behaviours.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p02] Recordings of Schweitzer playing the music of Bach are available on CD.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p02] In 1934 and 1935 he resided in Britain, delivering the Gifford Lectures at Edinburgh University, and those on *Religion in Modern Civilization* at Oxford and London.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p02] He had originally conducted trials for recordings for His Master's Voice on the organ of the old Queen's Hall in London.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p02] These records did not satisfy him, the instrument being too harsh.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p02] In mid-December 1935, he began to record for Columbia Records on the organ of All Hallows, Barking-by-the-Tower, London.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p02] These recordings were made in the course of a fortnight in October 1936.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p02] Schweitzer developed a technique for recording the performances of Bach's music; or perhaps engineers developed it to record his performances.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p02] Known as the "Schweitzer technique", it is a slight improvement on what is commonly known as mid-side.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p02] The mid-side sees a figure-8 microphone pointed off-axis, perpendicular to the sound source.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p02] Then a single cardioid microphone is placed on axis, bisecting the figure-8 pattern.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p02] The signal from the figure-8 is muted, panned hard left and right, one of the signals being flipped out of polarity.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p02] In the Schweitzer method, the figure-8 is replaced by two small diaphragm condenser microphones pointed directly away from each other.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p02] The information that each capsule collects is unique, unlike the identical out-of-polarity information generated from the figure-8 in a regular mid-side.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p02] The on-axis microphone is often a large diaphragm condenser.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p02] The technique has since been used to record many modern instruments.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p02] Altogether his early Columbia discs included 25 records of Bach and eight of César Franck.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p02] Later recordings were made at **Parish church, Günsbach**: These recordings were made by C.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p02] Schweitzer was being filmed in Günsbach for the documentary "Albert Schweitzer".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p02] Fine originally self-released the recordings but later licensed the masters to Columbia.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p02] The above were released in the United States as Columbia Masterworks boxed set SL-175.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/albert-schweitzer-p02] The Greek author Nikos Kazantzakis dedicated his novel The Poor Man of Assisi to him.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Leopold was influential in the development of modern environmental ethics and in the movement for wilderness conservation.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] His ethics of nature and wildlife preservation had a profound impact on the environmental movement, with his ecocentric or holistic ethics regarding land.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] He emphasized biodiversity and ecology and was a founder of the science of wildlife management.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Rand Aldo Leopold was born in Burlington, Iowa, on January 11, 1887.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] His father, Carl Leopold, was a businessman who made walnut desks and was first cousin to his wife, Clara Starker.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Charles Starker, who was Carl's father and Clara's uncle, came to the United States from Germany and studied engineering and architecture.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Rand Aldo was named after two of his father's business partners—C.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Rand and Aldo Sommers—although he eventually dropped the use of "Rand".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] The Leopold family included younger siblings Mary Luize, Carl Starker, and Frederic.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Leopold's first language was German, although he mastered English at an early age.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Aldo Leopold's early life was highlighted by the outdoors.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Carl would take his children on excursions into the woods and taught his oldest son woodcraft and hunting.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Aldo showed an aptitude for observation, spending hours counting and cataloging birds near his home.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] His sister Mary later said that even as a young child, "He was very much an outdoorsman, even in his extreme youth.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] He was always out climbing around the bluffs, or going down to the river, or going across the river into the woods." He attended Prospect Hill Elementary, where he ranked at the top of his class, and then, the overcrowded Burlington High School.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Every August, the family vacationed in Michigan on the forested Marquette Island in Lake Huron, which the children took to exploring.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] In 1900, Gifford Pinchot, head of the new Division of Forestry in the Department of Agriculture, donated money to Yale University to begin one of the nation's first forestry schools.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Hearing of this development, teenage Leopold decided he wanted to become a forester.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] His parents agreed to let him attend The Lawrenceville School, a preparatory college in New Jersey, to improve his chances of admission to Yale.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] The Burlington High School principal wrote in a reference letter to the headmaster at Lawrenceville saying that Leopold was "as earnest a boy as we have in school... painstaking in his work....
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Moral character above reproach." He arrived at his new school in January 1904, shortly before he turned 17.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] He was considered an attentive student, although he was again drawn to the outdoors.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Lawrenceville was suitably rural, and Leopold spent much time mapping the area and studying its wildlife.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Leopold studied at the Lawrenceville School for a year, during which time he was accepted to Yale.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Since the Yale School of Forestry granted only graduate degrees, Leopold first enrolled in Sheffield Scientific School's preparatory forestry courses for his undergraduate studies, in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] While Leopold was able to explore the woods and fields of Lawrenceville daily, sometimes to the detriment of his studying, at Yale he had little opportunity to do so; his studies and social life made his outdoor trips few and far between.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Leopold graduated from the Yale Forestry School in 1909.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] In 1909, Leopold was assigned to the Forest Service's District 3 in the Arizona and New Mexico territories.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] At first, he was a forest assistant at the Apache National Forest in the Arizona Territory.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] In 1911, he was transferred to the Carson National Forest in northern New Mexico.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Leopold was stationed in New Mexico until 1924 because he was developing the first comprehensive management plan for the Grand Canyon, writing the Forest Service's first game and fish handbook, and proposing Gila Wilderness Area, the first wilderness area in the Forest Service system.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Furthermore, Leopold encouraged many changes within New Mexico and Arizona through his time spent in the region developing these plans.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] In 1916, Leopold conducted a speaking tour across New Mexico to encourage the formation of wildlife protection associations among local sportsmen.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] The tour began in Silver City, where Leopold met Miles W.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Buford, who went on to establish the Sportsmen's Association of Southwestern New Mexico.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Leopold proposed the creation of a statewide organization, the New Mexico Game Protection Association (NMGPA), which gained support in several cities including Rincon, El Paso, Alamogordo, Cloudcroft, Carlsbad, Roswell, and Albuquerque.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] In March 1916, the NMGPA held its first convention, attracting over 1,000 members.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] The association adopted three goals: removing game warden appointments from political influence, establishing game refuges within national forests, and implementing a balance of predators.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Following the formation of the NMGPA, Leopold returned to his duties with the U.S.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] After the passage of the Term Permit Act, he began siting and surveying locations in Arizona for private recreational development.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] During this time, he also promoted and helped establish Game Protection Associations in Arizona towns such as Flagstaff, Springerville, Tucson, and Payson.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] In January 1918, Leopold became Secretary of the Albuquerque Chamber of Commerce.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] In this role, he supported various initiatives, including the inclusion of labor organizations in the chamber, the promotion of Hispanic and Pueblo architectural styles, and the drainage of parts of the Rio Grande Valley to expand agricultural land.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Leopold rejoined the Forest Service on August 1, 1919, as Assistant District Forester in Charge of Operations, overseeing Region 3, which included 11 national forests.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] During this period, he became concerned with soil erosion in areas such as the Prescott and Carson National Forests.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] In December 1923, he authored *The Watershed Handbook*, a guide for field staff addressing watershed management and recommending the regulation of livestock based on watershed conditions.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Just a few months into his new role, Leopold's superior, District Forester Paul Redington, left Region 3 and was succeeded by Frank C.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Pooler—who openly expressed doubts about Leopold's suitability for the position.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Pooler even arranged a new post for Leopold in a different region.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] However, Leopold stood his ground and declined the offer, choosing to stay in Albuquerque and New Mexico, where his family and numerous ongoing projects were deeply rooted.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Leopold's management plan was visionary for its time, emphasizing sustainable use and ecological preservation.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] He planned to make regulations with tourism, resource protection, recreational planning, and the long-term vision of the park.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] He felt that there needed to be a control of commercial enterprises, such as shops and concessions because he described them as "repugnant" to the canyon's natural character.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] He suggested there should be designated areas for visitor facilities to minimize environmental disruption.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Additionally, He advocated for the cleanup of garbage and sewage to restore the Colorado River's water quality.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Previously, there was history of people dumping garbage in the river.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] He emphasized preserving the canyon's geological and ecological features, including its stratified rock formations and native flora and fauna.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Leopold's plan for recreational planning was to outline strategies for “primitive recreation,” such as hiking, hunting, and fishing, to allow visitors to experience the canyon's wilderness without degrading it.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] He recommended trail development to improve access while protecting sensitive areas.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Finally, his long-term vision was to prioritized the “greatest good for the greatest number in the long run,” aligning with U.S.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] He laid the groundwork for future park management by advocating for a balance between human enjoyment and ecological health.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Wildlife management was largely unregulated, with game and fish populations often depleted due to overhunting, habitat destruction, and lack of coordinated oversight.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Leopold recognized the need for a systematic approach to manage wildlife resources.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] In the handbook, Leopold detailed a section on wildlife population management where he provided a guideline for monitoring and regulating game species, such as deer, elk, and fish, to prevent overharvesting.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] He emphasized sustainable hunting and fishing practices to maintain population health.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Additionally, he wrote a section on habitat conservation which he stressed the importance of preserving habitats, including forests, rivers, and wetlands, to support wildlife.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] He included recommendations for mitigating the impacts of grazing and logging on game and fish habitats.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] In a section about ecological balance, he introduced early concepts of predator-prey dynamics reflecting on his observations of ecological consequences when predators like wolves were eradicated.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] He advocated for a holistic approach to land management considering wildlife as part of the broader ecosystem.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Forest Service rangers to collect data on wildlife populations and enforce regulations.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] He proposed coordination with local communities and hunters to promote conservation awareness.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] In 1921, Leopold published an article in the *Journal of Forestry* titled “The Wilderness and Its Place in Forest Recreational Policy,” arguing for the preservation of roadless areas within national forests.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] He proposed the Gila as a prime candidate, envisioning it as a space free from roads, motorized vehicles, and industrial development.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] He recommended setting aside 750,000 acres of the Gila National Forest headwaters, an area characterized by canyons, mesas, and diverse wildlife, including elk, deer, and trout.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Leopold's proposal gained traction, and in 1924, the Forest Service approved the designation of 755,000 acres as the Gila Wilderness Area, the first such area in the world.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Leopold saw the Gila as a living laboratory for ecological health, where natural processes like predator-prey dynamics could unfold without human interference.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] This reflected his early understanding of trophic cascades, later detailed in his essay “Thinking Like a Mountain.” He also valued the Gila for its cultural significance, offering a space for Americans to reconnect with the frontier experience through self-reliant recreation.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] On April 5, 1923, he was elected an associate member (now called "professional member") of the Boone and Crockett Club, a wildlife conservation organization founded by Theodore Roosevelt and George Bird Grinnell.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] In 1924, he accepted transfer to the U.S.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Forest Products Laboratory in Madison, Wisconsin, and became an associate director.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] In 1933, he was appointed Professor of Game Management in the Agricultural Economics Department at the University of Wisconsin, the first such professorship of wildlife management.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] At the same time he was named Research Director of the University of Wisconsin–Madison Arboretum.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Leopold and other members of the first Arboretum Committee initiated a research agenda around re-establishing "original Wisconsin" landscape and plant communities, particularly those that predated European settlement, such as tallgrass prairie and oak savanna.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Under the Oberlaender Trust of the Carl Schurz Memorial Foundation, Leopold was part of the 1935 group of six U.S.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Forest Service associates who toured the forests of Germany and Austria.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Leopold was invited specifically to study game management, and this was his first and only time abroad.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] His European observations would have a significant impact on his ecological thinking, leading him to view the German policies in favor of blocks of monoculture trees in straight lines as a cautionary tale leading to soil degradation and an overall loss of biodiversity.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] After 1935, Leopold was no longer working for the U.S.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Forest Service; he had left the agency in 1928 to work independently and later became a professor at the University of Wisconsin.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Leopold married Estella Bergere, the daughter of a well known ranching family in New Mexico, in northern New Mexico in 1912 and they had five children together.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] They lived in a modest two-story home close to the UW–Madison campus.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] His children followed in his footsteps as teachers and naturalists: Aldo Starker Leopold (1913–1983) was a wildlife biologist and professor at UC Berkeley; Luna B.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Leopold purchased 80 acres in the sand country of central Wisconsin.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] The once-forested region had been logged, swept by repeated fires, overgrazed by dairy cows, and left barren.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] He put his theories to work in the field and eventually set to work writing his best-selling *A Sand County Almanac* (1949) which was finished just prior to his death.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Aldo Leopold died from a heart attack on April 21, 1948, while helping his neighbors control a grass fire by his farm in Baraboo, Wisconsin.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Leopold's home is an official landmark of the city of Madison.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Early on, Leopold was assigned to hunt and kill bears, wolves, and mountain lions in New Mexico.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Local ranchers hated these predators because of livestock losses, but Leopold came to respect the animals.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] One day after fatally shooting a wolf, Leopold reached the animal and was transfixed by a "fierce green fire dying in her eyes." That experience changed him and put him on the path toward an ecocentric outlook.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] He developed an ecological ethic that replaced the earlier wilderness ethic that stressed the need for human dominance.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] His rethinking the importance of predators in the balance of nature has resulted in the return of bears and mountain lions to New Mexico wilderness areas.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] By the early 1920s, Leopold had concluded that a particular kind of preservation should be embraced in the national forests of the American West.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] He was prompted to this by the rampant building of roads to accommodate the "proliferation of the automobile" and the related increasingly heavy recreational demands placed on public lands.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] He was the first to employ the term "wilderness" to describe such preservation.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Over the next two decades, he added ethical and scientific rationales to his defense of the wilderness concept.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Leopold believed that it is easier to maintain wilderness than to create it.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Leopold thus rejected the utilitarianism of conservationists such as Theodore Roosevelt.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] By the 1930s, Leopold had become one of the first Americans to publish extensively on the startup discipline of wildlife management.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] He advocated the scientific management of wildlife habitats by both public and private landholders rather than a reliance on game refuges, hunting laws, and other methods intended to protect specific species of desired game.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] The concept of "wilderness" also took on a new meaning; Leopold no longer saw it as a hunting or recreational ground, but as an arena for a healthy biotic community, including wolves and mountain lions.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] In 1935, he helped found the Wilderness Society, dedicated to expanding and protecting the nation's wilderness areas.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] He regarded the society as "one of the focal points of a new attitude—an intelligent humility toward Man's place in nature." Science writer Connie Barlow says Leopold wrote eloquently from a perspective that today would be called Religious Naturalism.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Though often forgotten, thinking about population dynamics and consumption also shaped Leopold's ecological vision in profound ways.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] By studying wildlife population fluctuations, Leopold extended many of the ideas about carrying capacity and environmental degradation that Raymond Pearl and Edward Murray East had articulated, and these ideas, in turn, shaped his path-breaking ideas of ecological interconnection.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Moreover, although later readers associate Leopold with wildlife ecology, his career helps show how Malthusian ideas of human society intertwined and overlapped with ideas of nature.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] He was greatly influenced by ecologists who themselves gleaned ideas from Malthusian models of human society, and himself often thought of human events—especially the Great Depression and World War II—in terms of the models of population and consumption that he was developing for animals.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] One of the most influential books for Leopold during that period was *Our Vanishing Wildlife* by William Temple Hornaday.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] As one of the earliest works dedicated entirely to the threats facing wild game populations this book significantly shaped Leopold's views.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] The book sharpened his focus on the importance of game protection, a concern that would remain central to his thinking for many years to come.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Leopold's nature writing is notable for its simple directness.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] His portrayals of various natural environments through which he had moved, or had known for many years, displayed impressive intimacy with what exists and happens in nature.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] This includes detailed diaries and journals of his Forest Service activity, hunting and field experience, as well as observations and activities at his Sand County farm.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] He offered frank criticism of the harm he believed was frequently done to natural systems (such as land) out of a sense of a culture or society's sovereign ownership over the land base – eclipsing any sense of a community of life to which humans belong.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] The book was published in 1949, shortly after Leopold's death.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] It was structured in a series of monthly essays where he went in depth about land ethics and nature.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Several of these monthly essays were accompanied with sketches from the different landscapes and plants he found.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Additionally, he would have philosophical segments that would contribute to his land ethic concepts.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Thinking Like a Mountain was originally written during World War II and shows that Leopold's thinking was shaped by that global cataclysm.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] In "The Land Ethic", a chapter in *A Sand County Almanac*, Leopold delves into conservation in "The Ecological Conscience" section.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] He wrote: "Conservation is a state of harmony between men and land." He noted that conservation guidelines at the time boiled down to: "obey the law, vote right, join some organizations, and practice what conservation is profitable on your own land; the government will do the rest." (p.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Aldo Leopold's contributions to conservation, particularly his role in establishing the Gila Wilderness Area, are deeply intertwined with the evolution of his philosophical views.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] In the early 20th century, Leopold's work with the U.S.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Forest Service in the American Southwest was grounded in the agency's utilitarian ethos, which prioritized resource extraction and economic productivity.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] As a forester in Arizona and New Mexico, Leopold initially approached wildlife management with a focus on maximizing game species for human benefit, a perspective aligned with the Progressive Era's emphasis on efficient resource use.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Leopold's philosophy began to evolve in the 1910s and 1920s, driven by field observations, ecological consequences of his early practices, and intellectual growth.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] A pivotal moment in Leopold's transformation occurred around 1909–1910, during his early years in the Apache National Forest.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] In his essay “Thinking Like a Mountain”, Leopold recounts shooting a wolf and watching it die, observing “a fierce green fire” in its eyes.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] This visceral experience, coupled with witnessing the subsequent ecological fallout, profoundly altered his perspective.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] The incident highlighted the role of predators in maintaining ecological balance.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Without wolves, deer populations surged, overgrazing vegetation and triggering a cascade of environmental damage, including soil erosion and loss of biodiversity.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Leopold realized that “the mountain” required all its components—predators, prey, and plants—to function healthily.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] This moment marked a shift from viewing wildlife in isolation to understanding ecosystems as dynamic, interdependent systems.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] It planted the seed for his later ecocentric philosophy, where no single species, including humans, could be prioritized at the expense of the whole.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] In "Marshland Elegy", an excerpt from *A Sand County Almanac,* Leopold describes the process of destruction for American marshland as well as the efforts to reinvigorate those marshlands after that destruction.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Leopold speak both to the way in which the halting of farmland development in these areas represents positive change for the cranes and other wildlife that relies on marshes as well as the limitations of the strategies implemented by conservationists in the issue.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Leopold criticized conservation strategy in that to make the public cherish the communities we conserve they need to "see and fondle" them which can make the conservation effort self-defeating.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] At the time this essay was written Sandhill Cranes had dwindled to merely 25 breeding pairs in Wisconsin, luckily since then the crane population has recovered with the midwest now being home to over 15,000 sandhill cranes.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] These efforts were inspired by this essay and carried out by the Aldo Leopold foundation.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] These efforts give a positive example to be looked to for future conservation efforts.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Game Management is deemed Leopold's most important work as it founded a new science by combining the likes of agriculture, biology, ecology, and other sciences.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] This book brought about a revolution within conservation and placed Leopold as the founder of the Department of Game Management at The University of Wisconsin.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] For more than 40 years after its publication, it was the leading textbook in the field of wildlife management.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Published nearly 45 years after the death of Leopold, The River of the Mother of God, includes 59 essays drawn from Leopold's unpublished manuscripts found at The University of Wisconsin and Leopold's overlooked published work.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] This collection is titled after one of Leopold's most popular essays from 1924, “The River of the Mother of God,” but it spans Leopold's life discussing themes of wilderness preservation, ecology, agriculture, land ethics, and natural esthetics from his teenage years until his last years.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] This work dives into a deeper view of Leopold and shows the lasting impact he made on the field of conservation.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] In *A Sand County Almanac*, Aldo Leopold's essay “A Man’s Leisure Time” provides us with a thoughtful examination of how leisure enriches our lives by deepening our connection with nature.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Leopold believed that how one spends their free time is a good indicator of one's intelligence and character.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Leopold states, “How miserable are the idle hours of the ignorant man!” contributing to his idea that leisure time is meaningful and it is important to take in the nature around when present with the opportunity.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] According to Leopold, leisure activities should not be relaxing time but ways to achieve personal growth and understanding.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] He describes hobbies as "a defiance of the contemporary," suggesting that they allow individuals to step away from the relentless pace of modern life and engage in activities that are rewarding and enriching.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Leopold highlights that such pursuits, whether it's collecting fossils or cultivating a garden, can lead to a profound appreciation of the land and how important and amazing nature is.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] In this chapter, Mr.Leopold encourages the reader to consider what they do with their free or leisure time in their life.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Leopold advocates for activities that promote a deeper understanding of the natural world.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] In 1933, Aldo Leopold became Professor of Game Management at the University of Wisconsin-Madison, the first position of its kind in the country.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Through his contributions to and knowledge of the field, he developed curricula and ran the program, which was eventually redubbed Wildlife Ecology.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] "Game Management" during this time meant the scientific study and the practical application of techniques for maintaining a healthy wildlife population, especially those that are hunted for sport.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Through his expertise, the area of wildlife management grew from just managing populations within life to a larger egocialcal approach to managing wildlife population.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Game management was a branch of conservation biology to Aldo Leopold.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] He was concerned about the whole ecological balance of the environment and not just one species.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] He created a field that was hit every area ecology, policy, forestry, and ethics.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] He even published a textbook for his class titles "Game management", also published in 1933.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] In 1950 The Wildlife Society honored Leopold by creating an annual award in his name.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Furthermore, the foundation formed a Leopold Conservation Award to recognize farmers, forestland owners, and private land owners for inspirational conservation efforts and leadership within land ethics.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] The *Aldo Leopold Foundation* of Baraboo, Wisconsin, was founded in 1982 by Aldo and Estella Leopold's five children as a 501(c)3 not-for-profit conservation organization whose mission is "to foster the land ethic through the legacy of Aldo Leopold".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] The Aldo Leopold Foundation owns and manages the original Aldo Leopold Shack and Farm and 300 surrounding acres, in addition to several other parcels.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Its headquarters is the green-built *Leopold Center* where it conducts educational and land stewardship programs.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] The foundation also acts as the executor of Leopold's literary estate, encourages scholarship on Leopold, and serves as a clearinghouse for information regarding Leopold, his work, and his ideas.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] It provides interpretive resources and tours for thousands of visitors annually, distributes a curriculum about how to use Leopold's writing and ideas in environmental education.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] The center maintains a robust website and numerous print resources.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] In 2012, in collaboration with the United States Forest Service, the foundation and the Center for Humans and Nature released the first full-length film about Leopold, titled *Green Fire: Aldo Leopold and a Land Ethic for Our Time*.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] The film aired on public television stations across the nation and won a Midwest regional Emmy award in the documentary category.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] The Aldo Leopold Wilderness in New Mexico's Gila National Forest was named after him in 1980.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] The Leopold Center for Sustainable Agriculture was established in 1987 at Iowa State University in Ames.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Since its founding, it has pioneered new forms of sustainable agriculture practices.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Forest Service established the Aldo Leopold Wilderness Research Institute at the University of Montana, Missoula in 1993.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] The Aldo Leopold Neighborhood Historic District, which includes Leopold's former home in Albuquerque, New Mexico, was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2002.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] The Aldo Leopold Legacy Trail System, a system of 42 state trails in Wisconsin, was created by the state in 2007 to honor Leopold's contributions to the conservation and outdoor recreation.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] This trail covers more than 1,700 miles across the state of Wisconsin.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Many of the trails pass through forests, scenics natural areas, and state parks.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] There are signs, along the trails, to showcase information about Leopold's life, his conservation work, and natural information about the surrounding area.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] The Leopold Center for Sustainable Agriculture in Iowa, created through the 1987 Iowa Groundwater Protection Act is committed to "new ways to farm profitably while conserving natural resources as well as reducing negative environmental and social impacts".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] An organization, the Leopold Heritage Group, is "dedicated to promoting the global legacy of Aldo Leopold in his hometown of Burlington, Iowa." This groups preserves and shares Leopold's legacy by providing local events, educational programs, and conservation projects.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] The "Leopold Heritage Group", supports efforts to maintain Leopold-relates sites around the area for example, his childhood home and many places that he has explored as a child.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] In 1985, Leopold was inducted along with John Muir, a naturalist and preservationist, as the first inductees to the Wisconsin Conservation Hall of Fame.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] The Hall of Fame is located in Stevens Point, Wisconsin, it was created to recognize the individuals who have made important contributions to conserving the natural state of resources around the state.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] The Leopold Residence Hall at the University of Wisconsin-Madison was named after him.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Leopold's Preserve in Haymarket, Virginia was established in 2014.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] This preserve is a 380-acre park that is committed to preserving diverse ecosystems, natural scenes, and protecting threatened land from industrial and commercial development.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] Aldo Leopold is well known for being the founder of wildlife management, he played a key role in establishing ethics in the wildlife world.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/aldo-leopold] He was a driving force behind the creation of the Gila National Forest Wilderness, and his legacy lives on today as the Gila National Forest has been standing strong since 1924, when the National Forest was created.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] The word "Allah" now conveys the superiority or sole existence of one God, but among the pre-Islamic Arabs, Allah was the supreme deity and worshipped alongside lesser deities in a pantheon.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Many Jews, Christians, and early Muslims used "Allah" and "al-ilah" synonymously in Classical Arabic.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] The word is also frequently, albeit not exclusively, used by Bábists, Baháʼís, Mandaeans, Indonesian Christians, Maltese Christians, and Sephardic Jews, as well as by the Gagauz people.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] The etymology of the word *Allāh* has been discussed extensively by classical Arab philologists.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] The majority of scholars consider it to be derived from a contraction of the Arabic definite article *al-* and *ilāh* "deity, god" to *al-lāh* meaning "the deity, the God" as in the contraction of *al-ʾilāt* to *Allāt*.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] In some sources, the contracted and un-contracted forms are used interchangeably.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Originally, *ʾilāh* was used as an epithet for the West Semitic creator god *ʾIlu* (the Ugaritic version of El), before being adopted as the proper name itself for this god.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Semitic cognates of "Allāh" appear in Semitic languages, such as the Aramaic *ʼElāh* (אלה) in the absolute form, and in its definite/emphatic form, *ʼElāhā* (אלהא), as in reflected in Biblical Aramaic.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Also Syriac ܐܲܠܵܗܵܐ (*ʼAlāhā*), both meaning simply "god", or "deity", used by both monotheists and pagans.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Others are Akkadian *ʾilum*, Ugartic *ʾilu*, and Phoenician *ʾl*.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] A minority hypothesis posits that *Allah* is a loanword from the Syriac *Alāhā*.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] A more likely theory is that, it is an adaptation of the word to the phonetic structure of Arabic.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Whether or not *Allah* can be considered as the personal name of God became disputed in contemporary scholarship.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Other Muslims scholars proposed that the term derives from *wilah* ('the object of mystery') since the nature of God is a mystery and incomprehensible for humans.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] In Islamic usage and theology, *Allah* is God's most unique, proper name, and referred to as *Lafẓ al-Jalālah* ('the Word of Majesty').
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Jahm bin Safwan was reported in later sources as holding that divine names, including “Allah”, were created rather than eternal.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Regional variants of the word *Allah* occur in both pagan and Christian pre-Islamic Arabian inscriptions.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] According to Marshall Hodgson, it seems that in the pre-Islamic Arabia, some Arab Christians undertook pilgrimages to the Kaaba, a pagan temple at that time, honoring Allah there as the God the Creator.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] In an inscription of Christian martyrion dated to 512, references to al-ilah (الاله) appear in both Arabic and Aramaic.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] The inscription opens with the phrase "By the Help of al-ilah".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Irfan Shahîd quoting the 10th-century encyclopedic collection Kitab al-Aghani notes that pre-Islamic Arab Christians have been reported to have raised the battle cry "*Ya La Ibad Allah*" (O slaves of Allah) to invoke each other into battle.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] According to Shahid, on the authority of 10th-century Muslim scholar Al-Marzubani, "Allah" was also mentioned in pre-Islamic Christian poems by some Ghassanid and Tanukhid poets in Syria and Northern Arabia.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Different theories have been proposed regarding the role of Allah in pre-Islamic polytheistic Meccan cults.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] According to Ibn Kathir, Arab idolaters considered Allah as an unseen god who created and controlled the Universe.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Pagans believed worship of humans or animals who had fortunate occurrences in their life brought them closer to God.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Pre-Islamic Meccans worshiped Allah alongside a host of lesser gods and those whom they called the "daughters of Allah".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] According to Islamic sources, the Meccans and their neighbors believed that the goddesses Al-lāt, Al-‘Uzzá, and Manāt, and in some cases the Angels, were the daughters of Allah.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Some authors have suggested that polytheistic Arabs used the name as a reference to a creator god or a supreme deity of their pantheon.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] According to one Islamic hypothesis, the Kaaba was originally built by Abraham and his son Ishmael for the worship of a single supreme god, Allah, to whom people were called on pilgrimages.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] However, this place of worship was filled by the Quraysh with as many as 360 idols about a century before Muhammad's time.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Some scholars have suggested that Allah may have represented a remote creator god who was gradually eclipsed by more particularized local deities.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] There is disagreement on whether Allah played a major role in the Meccan religious cult.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] No iconic representation of Allah is known to have existed.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Muhammad's father's name was *ʿAbd-Allāh* meaning "the slave of Allāh".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] The interpretation that Pre-Islamic Arabs once practiced Abrahamic religions is supported by some literary evidence, being the prevalence of Ishmael, whose God was that of Abraham, in pre-Islamic Arab culture.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] The worship of Allah, to the exclusion of all other deities, is the fundamental tenet of Islam, encapsulated in the testimony La ilaha illa Allah.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] The Quranic discourse with pagan Arabs did not aim to prove Allah's existence, but rather to purge it of polytheistic accretions, reinforcing this core monotheism.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Quran frames the worship of Allah as the shared mission of all prophets—including Abraham, Moses, and Jesus—and invites the People of the Book to unite under this *common word* (3:64).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] "The Qur'ān insists that Muhammad and his followers worship the same God as the Jews (29:46).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] The Qur'an's Allah is the same Creator God who covenanted with Abraham".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Francis Edward Peters states that the Qur'an portrays Allah as both more powerful and more remote than Yahweh, and as a universal deity, unlike Yahweh who closely follows Israelites.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Since the first centuries of Islam, Arabic-speaking commentators of Jewish, Christian, and Islamic faith used the term *Allah* as a generic term for the supreme being.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Saadia Gaon used the term *Allah* interchangeably with the term *ʾĔlōhīm*.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Theodore Abu Qurrah translates *theos* as *Allah* in his Bible, as in John 1:1 "the Word was with Allah".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Muslim commentators likewise used the term Allah for the Biblical concept of God.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Ibn Qutayba writes "You cannot serve both Allah and Mammon." However, Muslim translators of the Middle East, North Africa, and Asia rarely translated the Tetragrammaton, referring to the supreme being in Israelite tradition, as *Allah*.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Instead, most commentators either translated Yahweh as either *yahwah* or *rabb*, the latter corresponding to the Jewish custom to refer to Yahweh as *Adonai*.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] In contrast with pre-Islamic Arabian polytheism, as stated by Gerhard Böwering, God in Islam does not have associates and companions, nor is there any kinship between God and jinn.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Pre Islamic Arabs believed in a blind, powerful, unstoppable and insensible fate over which man had no control.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] This was replaced with the Islamic belief of a powerful yet benevolent and merciful God's control over man's life.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] In the early periods of Islam, the concept of God was established as a personal deity living in the heavens.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] This understanding developed over time under the influence of Islamic theology, acquiring a transcendent character.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] However, in contrast to this transcendent and absolute conception of God established among the elite, the public and Sufis maintained the traditional understanding of God.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Islamic theology emphasises the absolute uniqueness and singularity of God in his essence, attributes, qualities, and acts.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] This emphasis was made despite a number of verses and hadiths that offer analogies for God, and it was gradually established over time.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Instead, the term "mutashabih" was used for these verses, and the approach of "believing in the essence, not searching for its meaning" (Bila Kayf) was adopted.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Understandings and expressions contrary to these definitions (tanzih) were described as shirk, which is considered one of the greatest sins in Islam, and it was said that those who did so would leave the religion.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Islamic teachings, in accordance with the principle of *tawhid*, also condemn statements that imply God is something comparable to known and created things.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Most Qur'anic commentators, including al-Tabari (d.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] 1209), regard word *Allah* to be a proper noun i.e.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] (*ism' li-dhatih*), while other names denote attributes or adjectives known as the 99 Names of Allah (**al-asmā' al-ḥusná** lit. meaning: 'the beautiful names').
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] The most famous and frequently repeated names are "the Merciful" (*ar-Raḥmān*) and "the Compassionate" (**ar-Raḥīm**), *al-Aḥad* ("the One") and Al Hayy (the living one).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] In a Sufi practice known as *dhikr Allāh* (Arabic: ذِكر الله, lit.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] "Remembrance of God"), the Sufi chants and contemplates the name *Allah* or other associated divine names to Him while regulating his or her breath.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Islamic theology rejects definitions and expressions that imply a comparison between God and His creations, because He cannot be likened to His creations in any of His attributes.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] However, it is observed that many of these names are translated as "the most..." in a comparative mode, as in the expression **Allāhu ʾAkbar** (Arabic: اللّٰهُ أَكْبَر [ʔaɫ.ɫaː.hu ʔak.bar], lit.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] 'God is the greatest'), which is also used as an Islamic slogan.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] The Islamic tradition to use *Allah* as the personal name of God became contested in contemporary scholarship, including the question, whether or not the word *Allah* should be translated as *God*.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Umar Faruq Abd-Allah encouraged English-speaking Muslims to use God instead of Allah for the sake of finding "extensive middle ground we share with other Abrahamic and universal traditions".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Most Muslims use the Arabic phrase **in shā'a llāh** (meaning 'if God wills') untranslated after references to future events.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Muslim devotional practices encourage beginning things with the invocation of **bi-smi llāh** (meaning 'In the name of God').
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] The Christian Arabs of today have no other word for "God" than "Allah".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Similarly, the Aramaic word for "God" in the language of Assyrian Christians is *ʼĔlāhā*, or **Alaha**.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Arab Christians have used two forms of invocations that were affixed to the beginning of their written works.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] They adopted the Muslim **bismillāh**, and also created their own Trinitarian **bismillāh** as early as the 8th century.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] The Muslim **bismillāh** reads: "In the name of God, the Compassionate, the Merciful." The Trinitized **bismillāh** reads: "In the name of the Father and the Son and the Holy Spirit, One God." The Syriac, Latin, and Greek invocations do not have the words "One God" at the end.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] This addition was made to emphasize the monotheistic aspect of Trinitarian belief and also to make it more palatable to Muslims.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] The word *Allāh* is generally pronounced [ɑɫˈɫɑː(h)], exhibiting a heavy *lām*, [ɫ], a velarized alveolar lateral approximant, a marginal phoneme in Modern Standard Arabic.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Since the initial alef has no hamza, the initial [a] is elided when a preceding word ends in a vowel.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] If the preceding vowel is /i/, the *lām* is light, [l], as in, for instance, the *Basmala*.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] The history of the name *Allāh* in English was probably influenced by the study of comparative religion in the 19th century; for example, Thomas Carlyle (1840) sometimes used the term Allah but without any implication that Allah was anything different from God.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] However, in his biography of Muḥammad (1934), Tor Andræ always used the term *Allah*, though he allows that this "conception of God" seems to imply that it is different from that of the Jewish and Christian theologies.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Languages which may not commonly use the term *Allah* to denote God may still contain popular expressions which use the word.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] For example, because of the centuries long Muslim presence in the Iberian Peninsula, the word *ojalá* in the Spanish language and *oxalá* in the Portuguese language exist today, borrowed from Andalusi Arabic *law šá lláh* similar to *inshalla* (Arabic: إِنْ شَاءَ ٱللَّٰهُ).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] This phrase literally means 'if God wills'.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] The German poet Mahlmann used the form "Allah" as the title of a poem about the ultimate deity, though it is unclear how much Islamic thought he intended to convey.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Some Muslims retain the name "Allāh" untranslated in English, rather than using the English translation "God".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Christians in Malaysia and Indonesia use *Allah* to refer to God in the Malaysian and Indonesian languages (both of them standardized forms of the Malay language).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Mainstream Bible translations in the language use *Allah* as the translation of Hebrew *Elohim* (translated in English Bibles as "God").
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] This goes back to early translation work by Francis Xavier in the 16th century.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] The first dictionary of Dutch-Malay by Albert Cornelius Ruyl, Justus Heurnius, and Caspar Wiltens in 1650 (revised edition from 1623 edition and 1631 Latin edition) recorded *Allah*" as the translation of the Dutch word *Godt*.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Ruyl also translated the Gospel of Matthew in 1612 into the Malay language (an early Bible translation into a non-European language, made a year after the publication of the King James Version), which was printed in the Netherlands in 1629.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Then he translated the Gospel of Mark, published in 1638.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] For a time it became illegal for non-Muslims to use "Allah" after the country experienced a social and political upheaval in the face of the word being used by Malaysian Christians and Sikhs.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] The government of Malaysia in 2007 prohibited usage of the term *Allah* in any other but Muslim contexts, but the Malayan High Court in 2009 overturned the law, ruling it unconstitutional.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] While *Allah* had been used for the Christian God in Malay for more than four centuries, the contemporary controversy was triggered by usage of *Allah* by the Roman Catholic newspaper *The Herald*.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] The government appealed the court ruling, and the High Court suspended implementation of its verdict until the hearing of the appeal.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] In October 2013 the court ruled in favor of the government's ban.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] In early 2014 the Malaysian government confiscated more than 300 bibles for using the word to refer to the Christian God in Peninsular Malaysia.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] However, the use of *Allah* is not prohibited in the two Malaysian states of Sabah and Sarawak.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] The main reason it is not prohibited in these two states is that usage has been long-established and local Alkitab (Bibles) have been widely distributed freely in East Malaysia without restrictions for years.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Both states also do not have similar Islamic state laws as those in West Malaysia.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] In reaction to some media criticism, the Malaysian government has introduced a "10-point solution" to avoid confusion and misleading information.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] The 10-point solution is in line with the spirit of the 18- and 20-point agreements of Sarawak and Sabah.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] The word **Allāh** is always written without an *alif* to spell the **ā** vowel.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] This is because the spelling was established before Arabic spelling started regularly using **alif** to spell **ā**.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] However, in vocalized spelling, a small diacritic **alif** is added on top of the **shaddah** to indicate the pronunciation.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] In the pre-Islamic Zabad inscription, God is referred to by the term الاله, that is, alif-lam-alif-lam-ha.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] This presumably indicates **Al-'ilāh** means "the god", without **alif** for *ā*.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Many Arabic type fonts feature special ligatures for Allah.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Since Arabic script is used to write other texts rather than Koran only, rendering **lām** + **lām** + **hā'** as the previous ligature is considered faulty which is the case with most common Arabic typefaces.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Unicode has a code point reserved for **Allāh**, U+FDF2 ﷲ ARABIC LIGATURE ALLAH ISOLATED FORM, in the Arabic Presentation Forms-A block, which exists solely for "compatibility with some older, legacy character sets that encoded presentation forms directly"; this is not recommended for new text.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] Instead, the word **Allāh** should be represented by its individual Arabic letters, while modern font technologies will generate the desired ligature.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] The calligraphic variant of the word used as the emblem of Iran is encoded in Unicode, in the Miscellaneous Symbols range, at code point U+262B (☫).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/allah] The flags that include the word are also present in the regional indicator symbols of Unicode: 🇮🇶, 🇸🇦, 🇦🇫, 🇮🇷, 🇺🇿.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek was the language of Homer and of fifth-century Athenian historians, playwrights, and philosophers.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] It has contributed many words to English vocabulary and has been a standard subject of study in educational institutions of the Western world since the Renaissance.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] This article primarily contains information about the Epic and Classical periods of the language, which are the best-attested periods and considered most typical of Ancient Greek.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek comprised several dialects, such as Attic, Ionic, Doric, Aeolic, and Arcadocypriot; among them, Attic Greek became the basis of Koine Greek.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Just like Koine is often included in Ancient Greek, conversely, Mycenaean Greek is usually treated separately and not always included in Ancient Greek – reflecting the fact that Greek in the first millennium BC is considered prototypical of Ancient Greek.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek was a pluricentric language, divided into many dialects.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] The main dialect groups are Attic and Ionic, Aeolic, Arcadocypriot, and Doric, many of them with several subdivisions.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Some dialects are found in standardized literary forms in literature, while others are attested only in inscriptions.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] There are also several historical forms.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Homeric Greek is a literary form of Archaic Greek (derived primarily from Ionic and Aeolic) used in the epic poems, the *Iliad* and the *Odyssey*, and in later poems by other authors.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Homeric Greek had significant differences in grammar and pronunciation from Classical Attic and other Classical-era dialects.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] The origins, early form and development of the Hellenic language family are not well understood because of a lack of contemporaneous evidence.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Several theories exist about what Hellenic dialect groups may have existed between the divergence of early Greek-like speech from the common Proto-Indo-European language and the Classical period.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] They have the same general outline but differ in some of the detail.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] The only attested dialect from this period is Mycenaean Greek, but its relationship to the historical dialects and the historical circumstances of the times imply that the overall groups already existed in some form.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Scholars assume that major Ancient Greek period dialect groups developed no later than 1120 BC, at the time of the Dorian invasions—and that their first appearances as precise alphabetic writing began in the 8th century BC.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] The invasion would not be "Dorian" unless the invaders had some cultural relationship to the historical Dorians.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] The invasion is known to have displaced population to the later Attic-Ionic regions, who regarded themselves as descendants of the population displaced by or contending with the Dorians.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] The Greeks of this period believed there were three major divisions of all Greek people – Dorians, Aeolians, and Ionians (including Athenians), each with their own defining and distinctive dialects.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Allowing for their oversight of Arcadian, an obscure mountain dialect, and Cypriot, far from the center of Greek scholarship, this division of people and language is quite similar to the results of modern archaeological-linguistic investigation.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] (Southern Italy and Sicily) in the classical period.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] West vs. non-West Greek is the strongest-marked and earliest division, with non-West in subsets of Ionic-Attic (or Attic-Ionic) and Aeolic vs.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Arcadocypriot, or Aeolic and Arcado-Cypriot vs.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Arcadocypriot apparently descended more closely from the Mycenaean Greek of the Bronze Age.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Boeotian Greek had come under a strong Northwest Greek influence, and can in some respects be considered a transitional dialect, as exemplified in the poems of the Boeotian poet Pindar who wrote in Doric with a small Aeolic admixture.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Thessalian likewise had come under Northwest Greek influence, though to a lesser degree.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Pamphylian Greek, spoken in a small area on the southwestern coast of Anatolia and little preserved in inscriptions, may be either a fifth major dialect group, or it is Mycenaean Greek overlaid by Doric, with a non-Greek native influence.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Based on the conclusions drawn by several studies and findings such as Pella curse tablet, Emilio Crespo and most scholars suggest that ancient Macedonian was a Northwest Doric dialect, which shares isoglosses with its neighboring Thessalian dialects spoken in northeastern Thessaly.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Some have also suggested an Aeolic Greek classification.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] For example, fragments of the works of the poet Sappho from the island of Lesbos are in Aeolian.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Most of the dialect sub-groups listed above had further subdivisions, generally equivalent to a city-state and its surrounding territory, or to an island.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Doric notably had several intermediate divisions as well, into Island Doric (including Cretan Doric), Southern Peloponnesus Doric (including Laconian, the dialect of Sparta), and Northern Peloponnesus Doric (including Corinthian).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] All the groups were represented by colonies beyond Greece proper as well, and these colonies generally developed local characteristics, often under the influence of settlers or neighbors speaking different Greek dialects.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] After the conquests of Alexander the Great in the late 4th century BC, a new international dialect known as Koine or Common Greek developed, largely based on Attic Greek, but with influence from other dialects.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] This dialect slowly replaced most of the older dialects, although the Doric dialect has survived in the Tsakonian language, which is spoken in the region of modern Sparta.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Doric has also passed down its aorist terminations into most verbs of Demotic Greek.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] By about the 6th century AD, the Koine had slowly metamorphosed into Medieval Greek.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Phrygian is an extinct Indo-European language of West and Central Anatolia, which is regarded by current consensus to have been closely related to Greek.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Among Indo-European branches with living descendants, Greek is often argued to have the closest genetic ties with Armenian (see also Graeco-Armenian) and Indo-Iranian languages (see Graeco-Aryan).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek differs from Proto-Indo-European (PIE) and other Indo-European languages in certain ways.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] In phonotactics, ancient Greek words could end only in a vowel or /n s r/; final stops were lost, as in γάλα "milk", compared with γάλακτος "of milk" (genitive).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] The pronunciation of Ancient Greek was very different from that of Modern Greek.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek had long and short vowels; many diphthongs; double and single consonants; voiced, voiceless, and aspirated stops; and a pitch accent.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] In Modern Greek, all vowels and consonants are short.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Many vowels and diphthongs once pronounced distinctly are pronounced as /i/ (iotacism).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Some of the stops and glides in diphthongs have become fricatives, and the pitch accent has changed to a stress accent.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Many of the changes took place in the Koine Greek period.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] The writing system of Modern Greek, however, does not reflect all pronunciation changes.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] The examples below represent Attic Greek in the 5th century BC.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Ancient pronunciation cannot be reconstructed with certainty, but Greek from the period is well documented, and there is little disagreement among linguists as to the general nature of the sounds that the letters represent.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] /oː/ raised to [uː], probably by the 4th century BC.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Greek, like all of the older Indo-European languages, is highly inflected.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] It is highly archaic in its preservation of Proto-Indo-European forms.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] In ancient Greek, nouns (including proper nouns) have five cases (nominative, genitive, dative, accusative, and vocative), three genders (masculine, feminine, and neuter), and three numbers (singular, dual, and plural).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Verbs have four moods (indicative, imperative, subjunctive, and optative) and three voices (active, middle, and passive), as well as three persons (first, second, and third) and various other forms.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Verbs are conjugated through seven combinations of tenses and aspect (generally simply called "tenses"): the present, future, and imperfect are imperfective in aspect; the aorist, present perfect, pluperfect and future perfect are perfective in aspect.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Most tenses display all four moods and three voices, although there is no future subjunctive or imperative.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Also, there is no imperfect subjunctive, optative or imperative.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] The infinitives and participles correspond to the finite combinations of tense, aspect, and voice.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] The indicative of past tenses adds (conceptually, at least) a prefix /e-/, called the augment.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] This was probably originally a separate word, meaning something like "then", added because tenses in PIE had primarily aspectual meaning.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] The augment is added to the indicative of the aorist, imperfect, and pluperfect, but not to any of the other forms of the aorist (no other forms of the imperfect and pluperfect exist).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] The two kinds of augment in Greek are syllabic and quantitative.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] The syllabic augment is added to stems beginning with consonants, and simply prefixes *e* (stems beginning with *r*, however, add *er*).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Some verbs augment irregularly; the most common variation is *e* → *ei*.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] The irregularity can be explained diachronically by the loss of *s* between vowels, or that of the letter *w*, which affected the augment when it was word-initial.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] In verbs with a preposition as a prefix, the augment is placed not at the start of the word, but between the preposition and the original verb.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] For example, προσ(-)βάλλω (I attack) goes to προσ**έ**βαλoν in the aorist.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] However compound verbs consisting of a prefix that is not a preposition retain the augment at the start of the word: αὐτο(-)μολῶ goes to **ηὐ**τομόλησα in the aorist.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Following Homer's practice, the augment is sometimes not made in poetry, especially epic poetry.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] The augment sometimes substitutes for reduplication; see below.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Almost all forms of the perfect, pluperfect, and future perfect reduplicate the initial syllable of the verb stem.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Irregular duplication can be understood diachronically.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] For example, *lambanō* (root *lab*) has the perfect stem *eilēpha* (not **lelēpha*) because it was originally *slambanō*, with perfect *seslēpha*, becoming *eilēpha* through compensatory lengthening.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Reduplication is also visible in the present tense stems of certain verbs.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] These stems add a syllable consisting of the root's initial consonant followed by *i*.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] A nasal stop appears after the reduplication in some verbs.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] The earliest extant examples of ancient Greek writing (c.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] 1450 BC) are in the syllabic script Linear B.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Beginning in the 8th century BC, however, the Greek alphabet became standard, albeit with some variation among dialects.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Early texts are written in boustrophedon style, but left-to-right became standard during the classic period.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Modern editions of ancient Greek texts are usually written with accents and breathing marks, interword spacing, modern punctuation, and sometimes mixed case, but these were all introduced later.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] The beginning of Apology by Plato exemplifies Attic Greek from the Classical period of ancient Greek.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] How you, men of Athens, are feeling under the power of my accusers, I do not know: actually, even I myself almost forgot who I was because of them, they spoke so persuasively.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] And yet, loosely speaking, nothing they have said is true.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] The study of Ancient Greek in European countries in addition to Latin occupied an important place in the syllabus from the Renaissance until the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] This was true as well in the United States, where many of the nation's founders received a classically based education.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Latin was emphasized in American colleges, but Greek also was required in the colonial and early national eras, and the study of ancient Greece became increasingly popular in the mid-to-late nineteenth century, the age of American philhellenism.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] In particular, female intellectuals of the era designated the mastering of ancient Greek as essential in becoming a "woman of letters".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is still taught as a compulsory or optional subject especially at traditional or elite schools throughout Europe, such as public schools and grammar schools in the United Kingdom.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] In 2006/07, 15,000 pupils studied ancient Greek in Germany according to the Federal Statistical Office of Germany, and 280,000 pupils studied it in Italy.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] It is a compulsory subject alongside Latin in the humanities branch of the Spanish Baccalaureate.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is taught at most major universities worldwide, often combined with Latin as part of the study of classics.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] In 2010 it was offered in three primary schools in the UK, to boost children's language skills, and was one of seven foreign languages which primary schools could teach 2014 as part of a major drive to boost education standards.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is taught as a compulsory subject in all gymnasiums and lyceums in Greece.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] It appears to have ceased in 2010, having failed to gain the recognition and acceptance of teachers.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Its first issue appeared in April 2015 as an annex to *Hebdomada Aenigmatum*.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Alfred Rahlfs included a preface, a short history of the Septuagint text, and other front matter translated into ancient Greek in his 1935 edition of the Septuagint; Robert Hanhart also included the introductory remarks to the 2006 revised Rahlfs–Hanhart edition in the language as well.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] *Akropolis World News* reports weekly a summary of the most important news in ancient Greek.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is also used by organizations and individuals, mainly Greek, who wish to denote their respect, admiration or preference for the use of this language.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] This use is sometimes considered graphical, nationalistic or humorous.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] In any case, the fact that modern Greeks can still wholly or partly understand texts written in non-archaic forms of ancient Greek shows the affinity of the modern Greek language to its ancestral predecessor.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is often used in the coinage of modern technical terms in the European languages: see English words of Greek origin.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/ancient-greek] Latinized forms of ancient Greek roots are used in many of the scientific names of species and in scientific terminology.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/animal-liberation-book] A revised edition, *Animal Liberation Now*, was released in 2023.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/animal-liberation-book] In *Animal Liberation*, Singer argues against what he calls speciesism: discrimination on the grounds that a being belongs to a certain species.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/animal-liberation-book] He holds the interests of all beings capable of suffering to be worthy of equal consideration and that giving lesser consideration to beings based on their species is no more justified than discrimination based on skin color.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/animal-liberation-book] He argues that animals' rights should be based on their capacity to feel pain instead of their intelligence.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/animal-liberation-book] Therefore, intelligence does not provide a basis for giving nonhuman animals any less consideration than such intellectually challenged humans.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/animal-liberation-book] Singer concludes that the most practical solution is to adopt a vegetarian or vegan diet.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/animal-liberation-book] He also condemns vivisection except where the benefit (in terms of improved medical treatment, etc.) outweighs the harm done to the animals used.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/animal-liberation-book] Activist Ingrid Newkirk wrote of *Animal Liberation*, "It forever changed the conversation about our treatment of animals.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/animal-liberation-book] It made people—myself included—change what we ate, what we wore, and how we perceived animals." Other activists who claim that their attitudes to animals changed after reading the book include Peter Tatchell and Matt Ball.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/animal-liberation-book] Singer has expressed regret that the book did not have more impact.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/animal-liberation-book] It's had effects around the margins, of course, but they have mostly been minor.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/animal-liberation-book] When I wrote it, I really thought the book would change the world.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/animal-liberation-book] I know it sounds a little grand now, but at the time the 1960s still existed for us.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/animal-liberation-book] It looked as if real changes were possible, and I let myself believe that this would be one of them.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/animal-liberation-book] All you have to do is walk around the corner to McDonald's to see how successful I have been.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/animal-liberation-book] The book has also received critical challenges to the utilitarian underpinnings of his theory towards animal rights.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/animal-liberation-book] In addition, Martha Nussbaum has argued that the capability approach provides a more adequate foundation of justice than Utilitarianism can supply.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/animal-liberation-book] Utilitarianism, Nussbaum argues, ignores adaptive preferences, elides the separateness of distinct persons, misidentifies valuable human/non-human emotions such as grief, and calculates according to "sum-rankings" rather than inviolable protection of intrinsic entitlements.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/animal-liberation-book] The moral philosopher Roger Scruton criticised Singer's works, including *Animal Liberation*, saying that they "contain little or no philosophical argument.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/animal-liberation-book] In the essay "Animal Liberation: A Personal View", Singer describes the personal background that led to his adoption of the views he sets out in *Animal Liberation*.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/animal-liberation-book] His interest was sparked following a lunch in 1970 with a fellow Oxford graduate student, Richard Keshen, who avoided meat.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/animal-liberation-book] A revised edition, titled *Animal Liberation Now: The Definitive Classic Renewed*, was released on 23 May 2023, featuring a new foreword by Yuval Noah Harari.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/animal-liberation-book] Two-thirds of the book consists of entirely new material, and it also documents changes in animal welfare since the book's original publication, along with other developments, such as the impact of meat consumption on climate and on the risk of spreading dangerous new viruses.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Advocates of biocentrism often promote the preservation of biodiversity, animal rights, and environmental protection.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] The term has also been employed by advocates of "left biocentrism", which combines deep ecology with an "anti-industrial and anti-capitalist" position (according to David Orton *et al.*).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] In the simplest of terms as well as form, biocentrism is the belief that all living organisms, without exception, individually possess equal value and the same exact right to live, requiring identical moral treatment, regard, and prioritization.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Usually, the term biocentrism encompasses all environmental ethics that "extend the status of moral object from human beings to all living things in nature".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Biocentric ethics calls for a rethinking of the relationship between humans and nature.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Biocentrists observe that all species have inherent value, and that humans are not "superior" to other species in a moral or ethical sense.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] All species are part of a system of interdependence.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] All living organisms pursue their own "good" in their own ways.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Human beings are not inherently superior to other living things.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] The most important of these four main pillars is likely the idea that human beings are not inherently superior to other living things.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] People have divergent views on many specific aspects of almost everything.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Not all biocentrists even subscribe to the abstract concept of value, which is why heavy emphasis is placed on the fourth pillar.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Biocentrism views individual species as parts of the living biosphere.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] It observes the consequences of reducing biodiversity on both small and large scales and points to the inherent value all species have to the environment.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] The environment is seen for what it is; the biosphere within which we live and depend on the maintaining of its diversity for our health.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] From these observations the ethical points are raised.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Biocentric ethics differs from classical and traditional ethical thinking.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Rather than focusing on strict moral rules, as in Classical ethics, it focuses on attitudes and character.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] In contrast with traditional ethics, it is nonhierarchical and gives priority to the natural world rather than to humankind exclusively.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Biocentric ethics includes Albert Schweitzer's ethics of "Reverence for Life", Peter Singer's ethics of Animal Liberation and Paul W.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Taylor's ethics of biocentric egalitarianism.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Albert Schweitzer's "reverence for life" principle was a precursor of modern biocentric ethics.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] In contrast with traditional ethics, the ethics of "reverence for life" denies any distinction between "high and low" or "valuable and less valuable" life forms, dismissing such categorization as arbitrary and subjective.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Conventional ethics concerned itself exclusively with human beings—that is to say, morality applied only to interpersonal relationships—whereas Schweitzer's ethical philosophy introduced a "depth, energy, and function that differ[s] from the ethics that merely involved humans".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] "Reverence for life" was a "new ethics, because it is not only an extension of ethics, but also a transformation of the nature of ethics".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Similarly, Peter Singer argues that non-human animals deserve the same equality of consideration that we extend to human beings.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Using membership in the species *Homo sapiens* as a criterion of moral importance is completely arbitrary.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Of the remaining criteria we might consider, only sentience is a plausible criterion of moral importance.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Using sentience as a criterion of moral importance entails that we extend the same basic moral consideration (i.e.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] "basic principle of equality") to other sentient creatures that we do to human beings.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Therefore, we ought to extend to animals the same equality of consideration that we extend to human beings.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Singer's work, while notable in the canon of environmental ethics, should not be considered as fully biocentric.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Singer's ethics is extended from humans to nonhuman animals because the criterion for moral inclusion (sentience) is found in both humans and nonhuman animals, thus it would be arbitrary to deny it to nonhuman animals simply because they were not human.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] However, not all biological entities are sentient, consider: algae, plants and trees, fungi, lichens, mollusks, protozoa, for example.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] For an ethical theory to be biocentric, it must have a reason for extending ethical inclusion to the entire biosphere (as in Taylor and Schweitzer).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] The requirement for environmental ethics to move beyond sentience as criteria for inclusion in the moral realm is discussed in Tom Regan's 1981 paper "The Nature and Possibility of an Environmental Ethic".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Biocentrism is most commonly associated with the work of Paul W.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Taylor, especially his book *Respect for Nature: A Theory of Environmental Ethics* (1986).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Taylor maintains that biocentrism is an "attitude of respect for nature", whereby one attempts to make an effort to live one's life in a way that respects the welfare and inherent worth of all living creatures.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] This community consists of a system of interdependence between all members, both physically, and in terms of relationships with other species.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Every organism is a "teleological centre of life", that is, each organism has a purpose and a reason for being, which is inherently "good" or "valuable".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Humans are not inherently superior to other species.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Historian Donald Worster traces today's biocentric philosophies, which he sees as part of a recovery of a sense of kinship between man and nature, to the reaction by the British intelligencia of the Victorian era against the Christian ethic of dominion over nature.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] In 1859, Charles Darwin published his book *On the Origin of Species*.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] This publication sparked the beginning of biocentrist views by introducing evolution and "its removal of humans from their supernatural origins and placement into the framework of natural laws".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] The work of Aldo Leopold has also been associated with biocentrism.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] The essay "The Land Ethic" in Leopold's book *Sand County Almanac* (1949) points out that although throughout history women and slaves have been considered property, all people have now been granted rights and freedoms.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Leopold notes that today land is still considered property as people once were.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] He asserts that ethics should be extended to the land as "an evolutionary possibility and an ecological necessity".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] He argues that while people's instincts encourage them to compete with others, their ethics encourage them to co-operate with others.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] He suggests that "the land ethic simply enlarges the boundaries of the community to include soils, waters, plants, and animals, or collectively: the land".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] In a sense this attitude would encourage humans to co-operate with the land rather than compete with it.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Outside of formal philosophical works biocentric thought is common among pre-colonial tribal peoples who knew no world other than the natural world.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] The paradigm of biocentrism and the values that it promotes are beginning to be used in law.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] In recent years (as of 2011), cities in Maine, Pennsylvania, New Hampshire and Virginia have adopted laws that protect the rights of nature.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] The purpose of these laws is to prevent the degradation of nature, especially by corporations who may want to exploit natural resources and land space, and to also use the environment as a dumping ground for toxic waste.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] The first country to include rights of nature in its constitution is Ecuador (see 2008 Constitution of Ecuador).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Article 71 states that nature "has the right to integral respect for its existence and for the maintenance and regeneration of its life cycles, structure, functions and evolutionary processes".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] In Islam, biocentric ethics stem from the belief that all of creation belongs to Allah (God), not humans, and to assume that non-human animals and plants exist merely to benefit humankind leads to environmental destruction and misuse.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] As all living organisms exist to praise God, human destruction of other living things prevents the earth's natural and subtle means of praising God.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] The Qur'an acknowledges that humans are not the only all-important creatures and emphasizes a respect for nature.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Hinduism contains many elements of biocentrism.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] In Hinduism, humans have no special authority over other creatures, and all living things have souls ('atman').
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Brahman (God) is the "efficient cause" and Prakrti (nature), is the "material cause" of the universe.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] However, while Hinduism does not give the same direct authority over nature that the Judeo-Christian-Islamic god grants, they are subject to a "higher and more authoritative responsibility for creation".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] The most important aspect of this is the doctrine of Ahimsa (non-violence).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] The Yājñavalkya Smṛti warns, "the wicked person who kills animals which are protected has to live in hell fire for the days equal to the number of hairs on the body of that animal".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] The essential aspect of this doctrine is the belief that the Supreme Being incarnates into the forms of various species.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] The Hindu belief in Saṃsāra (the cycle of life, death and rebirth) encompasses reincarnation into non-human forms.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] It is believed that one lives 8,400,000 lifetimes before one becomes a human.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Each species is in this process of samsara until one attains moksha (liberation).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Another doctrinal source for the equal treatment of all life is found in the Rigveda.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] The Rigveda states that trees and plants possess divine healing properties.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] It is still popularly believed that every tree has a Vriksa-devata (a tree deity).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Trees are ritually worshiped through prayer, offerings, and the sacred thread ceremony.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] The Vriksa-devata worshiped as manifestations of the Divine.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Tree planting is considered a religious duty.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] The Jaina tradition exists in tandem with Hinduism and shares many of its biocentric elements.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Ahimsa (non-violence), the central teaching of Jainism, means more than not hurting other humans.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] It means intending not to cause physical, mental or spiritual harm to any part of nature.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] In the words of Mahavira: 'You are that which you wish to harm.' Compassion is a pillar of non-violence.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Jainism encourages people to practice an attitude of compassion towards all life.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] The principle of interdependence is also very important in Jainism.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] This states that all of nature is bound together, and that "if one does not care for nature one does not care for oneself.".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Another essential Jain teaching is self-restraint.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Jainism discourages wasting the gifts of nature, and encourages its practitioners to reduce their needs as far as possible.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] The Buddha's teachings encourage people "to live simply, to cherish tranquility, to appreciate the natural cycle of life".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Buddhism emphasizes that everything in the universe affects everything else.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] "Nature is an ecosystem in which trees affect climate, the soil, and the animals, just as the climate affects the trees, the soil, the animals and so on.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Although this holistic approach is more ecocentric than biocentric, it is also biocentric, as it maintains that all living things are important and that humans are not above other creatures or nature.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Within the Catholic tradition of Christian thought, Pope Benedict XVI noted that "the Church’s magisterium expresses grave misgivings about notions of the environment inspired by ecocentrism and biocentrism".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] This, he stated, was because "such notions eliminate the difference of identity and worth between the human person and other living things.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Biocentrism has faced criticism for a number of reasons.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Some of this criticism grows out of the concern that biocentrism is an anti-human paradigm and that it will not hesitate to sacrifice human well-being for the greater good.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Biocentrism has also been criticized for its individualism; emphasizing too much on the importance of individual life and neglecting the importance of collective groups, such as an ecosystem.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] A more complex form of criticism focuses on the contradictions of biocentrism.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Opposed to anthropocentrism, which sees humans as having a higher status than other species, biocentrism puts humans on a par with the rest of nature, and not above it.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] In his essay *A Critique of Anti-Anthropocentric Biocentrism* Richard Watson suggests that if this is the case, then "Human ways—human culture—and human actions are as natural as the ways in which any other species of animals behaves".
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] He goes on to suggest that if humans must change their behavior to refrain from disturbing and damaging the natural environment, then that results in setting humans apart from other species and assigning more power to them (to human beings).
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] This then takes us back to the basic beliefs of anthropocentrism.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Watson also claims that the extinction of species is "Nature's way" and that if humans were to instigate their own self-destruction by exploiting the rest of nature, then so be it.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] Therefore, he suggests that the real reason humans should reduce their destructive behavior in relation to other species is not because we are equals but because the destruction of other species will also result in our own destruction.
[src:biocentrism-ethics/biocentrism-ethics] This view also brings us back to an anthropocentric perspective.
